WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:09.000
The following is a conversation with Sean Kelly, a philosopher at Harvard specializing in existentialism and the philosophy of mind.

00:09.000 --> 00:15.000
This is the Lex Friedman podcast. To support it, please check out our sponsors in the description.

00:15.000 --> 00:20.000
And now, here's my conversation with Sean Kelly.

00:20.000 --> 00:34.000
Your interests are in postcontain European philosophy, especially phenomenology and existentialism. So let me ask, what to you is existentialism?

00:34.000 --> 00:38.000
So it's a hard question. I'm teaching a course on existentialism right now.

00:38.000 --> 00:39.000
You are.

00:39.000 --> 00:44.000
I am, yeah. Existentialism in literature and film, which is fun.

00:44.000 --> 00:56.000
I mean, the traditional thing to say about what existentialism is, is that it's a movement in mid 20th century, mostly French, some German philosophy.

00:56.000 --> 01:07.000
And some of the major figures associated with it are people like Jean-Paul Sartre and Camus, Simone de Beauvoir, maybe Martin Heidegger.

01:07.000 --> 01:13.000
But that's a weird thing to say about it, because most of those people denied that they were existentialists.

01:13.000 --> 01:19.000
And in fact, I think of it as a movement that has a much longer history.

01:19.000 --> 01:29.000
So when I try to describe what the core idea of existentialism is, it's an idea that you find expressed in different ways in a bunch of these people.

01:29.000 --> 01:42.000
One of the ways that it's expressed is that Sartre will say that existentialism is the view that there is no God and at least his form of existentialism.

01:42.000 --> 01:46.000
He calls it atheistic existentialism. There is no God.

01:46.000 --> 01:54.000
And since there is no God, there must be some other being around who does something like what God does.

01:54.000 --> 01:59.000
Otherwise, there wouldn't be any possibility for significance in a life.

01:59.000 --> 02:17.000
And that being is us. And the feature of us, according to Sartre and the other existentialists, that puts us in the position to be able to play that role is that we're the beings for whom, as Sartre says it, existence precedes essence.

02:17.000 --> 02:23.000
That's the catchphrase for existentialism. And then you have to try to figure out what it means.

02:23.000 --> 02:26.000
What is existence? What is presence? And what does precedes mean?

02:26.000 --> 02:30.000
Yeah, exactly. What is existence? What is essence? And what is precedes?

02:30.000 --> 02:35.000
And in fact, precedes is Sartre's way of talking about it and other people will talk about it differently.

02:35.000 --> 02:42.000
But here's the way Sartre thinks about it. This is not, I think, the most interesting way to think about it, but I'll get you started.

02:42.000 --> 02:54.000
Sartre says, there's nothing true about what it is to be you until you start existing, until you start living.

02:54.000 --> 03:11.000
And for Sartre, the core feature of what it is to be existing, the way we do, is to be making decisions, to be making choices in your life, to be sort of taking a stand on what it is to be you by deciding to do this or that.

03:11.000 --> 03:25.000
And the key feature of how to do that right, for Sartre, is to do it in the full recognition of the fact that when you make that choice, nobody is responsible for it other than you.

03:25.000 --> 03:36.000
So you don't make the choice because God tells you to. You don't make the choice because some utilitarian calculus about what it's right to do tells you to do.

03:36.000 --> 03:50.000
You don't make the choice because some other philosophical theory tells you to do it. There's literally nothing on the basis of which you make the choice other than the fact that in that moment, you're the one making it.

03:50.000 --> 03:59.000
You are conscious thinking being that made a decision. So all the questions about physics and free will are out the window.

03:59.000 --> 04:20.000
Yeah, that's right. If you were a determinist about the mind, if you were a physicalist about the mind, if you thought there was nothing to your choices other than the activity of the brain that's governed by physical laws, then there's some sense in which it would seem at any rate like you're not the ground of that choice.

04:21.000 --> 04:26.000
The ground of that choice was the physical universe and the laws that govern it, and then you'd have no responsibility.

04:26.000 --> 04:38.000
And so Sartre's view is that the thing that's special about us, used to be special about God, is that we're responsible for becoming the being that makes the choices that we do.

04:38.000 --> 04:53.000
And Sartre thinks that that's simultaneously empowering. I mean, it practically puts us in the place of God and also terrifying because what responsibility? How can you possibly take on that responsibility?

04:54.000 --> 05:11.000
And he thinks it's worse than that. He thinks that it's always happening. Everything that you do is the result of some choice that you've made, the posture that you sit in, the way you hold someone's gaze when you're having a conversation with them or not,

05:11.000 --> 05:24.000
the choice to make a note when someone says something or not make a note. Everything that you do presents you as a being who makes decisions and you're responsible for all of them.

05:24.000 --> 05:35.000
So it's constantly happening. And furthermore, there's no fact about you independent of the choices and actions you've performed.

05:36.000 --> 05:45.000
So you don't get to say, Sartre's example, I really am a great writer, just haven't written my great book yet. If you haven't written your great book, you're not a great writer.

05:45.000 --> 05:58.000
And so it's terrifying. It puts a huge burden on us. And that's why Sartre says on his view of existentialism, human beings are the beings that are condemned to be free.

05:59.000 --> 06:08.000
Our freedom consists in our ability and our responsibility to make these choices and to become someone through making them. And we can't get away from that.

06:08.000 --> 06:14.000
But to him, it's terrifying not liberating in the positive meaning of the word liberating.

06:14.000 --> 06:24.000
Well, so he thinks it should be liberating, but he thinks that it takes a very courageous individual to be liberated by it. Nietzsche, I think, thought something similar.

06:24.000 --> 06:39.000
I think Sartre is really coming out of a Nietzschean sort of tradition. But what's liberating about it, if it is, is also terrifying because it means in a certain way, you're the ground of your own being.

06:39.000 --> 06:49.000
You become what you do through existing. So that's one form of existentialism. That's a stark atheistic version of it. There's lots of other versions.

06:49.000 --> 07:01.000
But it's somehow organized around the idea that it's through living your life that you become who you are. It's not facts that are sort of true about you, independent of your living your life.

07:02.000 --> 07:14.000
But then if there's no God in that view, does any of the decisions matter? So how does existentialism differ from nihilism?

07:14.000 --> 07:25.000
Good. Okay. Great question. There was two different ways that you're asking it. Let me leave nihilism to the side for just a second and think about mattering.

07:25.000 --> 07:33.000
Or is there any way that you can criticize someone for doing, for living the way they do if you're an existentialist?

07:33.000 --> 07:34.000
Including yourself.

07:34.000 --> 07:44.000
Including yourself, yeah. Sartre addresses that and he says, yes, he says, there is a criticism that you can make of yourself or of others.

07:44.000 --> 07:50.000
And it's the criticism of living in such a way as to fail to take responsibility for your choices.

07:50.000 --> 08:04.000
He gives these two sort of amazing examples. I don't know if it reads as well as for us as it did in sort of mid 20th century Paris, but it's about a waiter.

08:04.000 --> 08:07.000
He gives this in his big book Being and Nothingness.

08:07.000 --> 08:21.000
And he says, so waiters played still do, I think, in a certain way in Paris. A big role in Parisian society to be a waiter involved having a certain kind of identity, being a certain way.

08:21.000 --> 08:33.000
Taking control of and charge of the experience of the people that you're waiting on, but also really being the authority, like knowing that this is the way it's supposed to go.

08:33.000 --> 08:53.000
And so Sartre imagines a waiter who does everything that a waiter is supposed to do, the perfect form of the waiter, except that you can somehow see in the way he's doing it that he's doing it because he believes that's the way a waiter should act.

08:54.000 --> 09:05.000
So there's some sense in which he's passing off the responsibility for his actions onto some idea of what those actions should be. He's not taking responsibility for it.

09:05.000 --> 09:12.000
He's sort of playing a role and the contours of the role are predetermined by someone other than him.

09:12.000 --> 09:25.000
So he starts acting in bad faith. And that's criticisable because it's acting in such a way as to fail to take responsibility for the kind of being Sartre thinks you are.

09:25.000 --> 09:35.000
So you're not taking responsibility. So that's one example. And I think any teenager, if you've ever met a teenager, you've known someone who does that.

09:35.000 --> 09:46.000
If teenagers try on roles, they think, if I dressed like this, I would be cool. So I'll dress like this. Or if I spoke like this or acted like this.

09:46.000 --> 09:56.000
And it's natural for a teenager who's trying to figure out what their identity is to go through a phase like that. But if you continue to do that, then you're really passing.

09:56.000 --> 10:16.000
That's one example. And the other example he gives is an example, not of passing off responsibility by pretending that someone else is the ground of your choice, but passing off responsibility by pretending that you might be able to get away with not making a choice at all.

10:16.000 --> 10:40.000
So he says, you're always everything you do is a result of your choices. And so he gives this other example. There you are on the first date, first date. And the date, the evening reaches moments when might be appropriate for one person to hold the hand of the other.

10:40.000 --> 10:57.000
That's the moment in the date where you are. And so you make a choice. You decide, I think it's that time and you hold the hand. And what should happen is that the other person also makes a choice on SART's view. Either they reject the hand, not that time.

10:57.000 --> 11:14.000
And I'm taking responsibility for that. Or they grasp the hand back. That's a choice. But there's a thing that sometimes happens, which is that the other person leaves the hand there cold, dead and clammy, neither rejecting it nor embracing it.

11:15.000 --> 11:36.000
And SART says, that's also bad faith. That's also acting as if we're kind of being that we're not, because it pretends that it's possible not to make a choice. And we're the beings who are always making choices. That was a choice. And you're pretending as if it's the kind of thing that you don't have to take responsibility for.

11:36.000 --> 11:52.000
So both of the examples you've given, there's some sense in which the social interactions between humans is the kind of moving away from the full responsibility that you as a human in the view of existentialism should take on.

11:52.000 --> 12:12.000
So like, isn't the basic conversation a delegation of responsibility? Just holding a hand there. You're putting some of the responsibility into the court of the other person. And for the waiter, if you're existing a society, you are generally trying on a role.

12:13.000 --> 12:34.000
All of us are trying on a role. Me wearing clothes is me trying on a role that I was told to try as opposed to walking around naked all the time. There's like standards of how you operate. And that's a decision that's not my own. That's me seeing what everyone else is doing and copying them.

12:34.000 --> 12:55.000
Yeah, exactly. So Sartre thinks that in the ideal, you should try to resist that. Other existentialists think that that's actually a clue to how you should live well. So Sartre says somewhere else, hell is other people.

12:55.000 --> 13:16.000
Why is hell other people for Sartre? Well, because other people are making choices also. And when other people make choices, they put some pressure on me to think that the choice they made is one that I should copy or one that I should sort of promote.

13:16.000 --> 13:43.000
But if I do it because they did it, then I'm in bad faith for Sartre. So it is as if Sartre's view is like we would be better if we were all alone. I mean, this is really simplifying Sartre's position. And this is really just mostly Sartre in a certain period of his formation. But anyhow, we can imagine that view. And I think there's something to the idea that Sartre is attracted to it, at least in the mid 40s.

13:44.000 --> 14:02.000
Can you dig into hell as other people? Is there some, obviously it's kind of almost like a literary, like you push the point strongly to really explore that point. But is there some sense in that other people ruin the experience of what it means to be human?

14:03.000 --> 14:25.000
I think for Sartre, the phenomenon is this. Like, it's not just that you wear clothes because people wear clothes in our society. Like you have a particular style. You wear a particular kind of clothes. And for Sartre, to have that style authentically in good faith rather than in bad faith, it has to come from you. You have to make the choice.

14:25.000 --> 14:48.000
But other people are making choices also. And like you're looking at their choices and you're thinking, that guy looks good. Maybe I could try that one on. And if you try it on because you were influenced by the fact that you thought that guy was doing it well, then there's some important sense in which, although that's a resource for a choice for you, it's also acting in bad faith.

14:48.000 --> 15:00.000
And God wouldn't do that, right? God wouldn't be influenced by other's decisions. And if that's the model, then that's, I think that's the sense in which he thinks hell is other people.

15:00.000 --> 15:05.000
What do you think parenting is then? It's like what, because God doesn't have a parent.

15:05.000 --> 15:06.000
Yeah.

15:06.000 --> 15:11.000
Aren't we significantly influenced first of all in the first few years of life?

15:11.000 --> 15:12.000
Absolutely.

15:12.000 --> 15:19.000
And even the teenager is resisting, learning through resistance.

15:19.000 --> 15:20.000
Absolutely.

15:20.000 --> 15:32.000
I mean, I think what you're pushing on is the intuition that the ideal that Sartre's aiming at is a kind of inhuman ideal.

15:32.000 --> 15:37.000
And there's many ways in which we're not like the traditional view of what God was.

15:37.000 --> 15:42.000
One is that we're not self-generating. We have parents.

15:42.000 --> 15:48.000
We're raised into traditions and social norms.

15:48.000 --> 15:55.000
And we're raised into an understanding of what's appropriate and inappropriate to do.

15:55.000 --> 16:01.000
And I think that's a deep intuition. I think that's exactly right.

16:01.000 --> 16:06.000
Martin Heidegger, who's the philosopher that Sartre thinks he's sort of taking this from,

16:06.000 --> 16:15.000
but I think Sartre's a kind of brilliant French misinterpretation of Heidegger's German phenomenological view.

16:15.000 --> 16:21.000
Heidegger says, a crucial aspect of what it is to be us is our thrownness.

16:21.000 --> 16:25.000
We're thrown into a situation. We're thrown into history.

16:25.000 --> 16:30.000
We're thrown into our parental lineage. And we don't choose it.

16:30.000 --> 16:33.000
That's stuff that we don't choose. We couldn't choose.

16:33.000 --> 16:38.000
If we were God and we existed outside of time, maybe, but we're not.

16:38.000 --> 16:43.000
We're finite in the sense that we have a beginning that we never chose.

16:43.000 --> 16:49.000
We have an end that we're often trying to resist or put off or something.

16:49.000 --> 16:55.000
And in between, there's a whole bunch of stuff that organizes us without our ever having made the choice

16:55.000 --> 17:00.000
and without the kind of being that could make the choice to allow it to organize us.

17:00.000 --> 17:04.000
We have a complicated relationship to that stuff.

17:04.000 --> 17:06.000
And I think we should talk about that at a certain point.

17:06.000 --> 17:12.000
But the first move is to say, Sartre's just got a sort of descriptive problem.

17:12.000 --> 17:19.000
He's missed this basic fact that there has to be an awful lot about us

17:19.000 --> 17:25.000
that's settled without our having made the choice to settle it that way.

17:25.000 --> 17:28.000
Right. The thrownness of life.

17:28.000 --> 17:29.000
Yeah.

17:29.000 --> 17:32.000
That's a fundamental part of life. You can't just escape it.

17:32.000 --> 17:34.000
Exactly. You can't escape it altogether.

17:34.000 --> 17:35.000
Altogether.

17:35.000 --> 17:37.000
Yeah, exactly. You can't escape it altogether.

17:37.000 --> 17:43.000
But nevertheless, you are riding a wave and you make a decision in the riding of the wave.

17:43.000 --> 17:48.000
You can't control the wave, but you should be, as you ride it,

17:48.000 --> 17:53.000
you should be making certain kinds of decisions and take responsibility for it.

17:53.000 --> 17:57.000
So why does this matter at all?

17:57.000 --> 17:59.000
The chain of decisions you make.

17:59.000 --> 18:03.000
Good. Well, because they constitute you, they make you the person that you are.

18:03.000 --> 18:06.000
So what's the opposite view?

18:06.000 --> 18:08.000
What's this view against?

18:08.000 --> 18:13.000
This view is against most of philosophy from Plato forward.

18:13.000 --> 18:22.000
Plato says in the Republic, it's a kind of myth, but he says people will understand their condition.

18:22.000 --> 18:29.000
Well, if we tell them this myth, he says, look, when you're born, there's just a fact about you.

18:29.000 --> 18:33.000
Your soul is either gold, silver, or bronze.

18:33.000 --> 18:37.000
Those are the three kinds of people there are, and you're born that way.

18:37.000 --> 18:42.000
If your soul is gold, then we should identify that and make you a philosopher king.

18:42.000 --> 18:46.000
And if your soul is silver, well, you're not going to be a philosopher king.

18:46.000 --> 18:50.000
You're not capable of it, but you could be a good warrior and we should make you that.

18:50.000 --> 18:53.000
And if your soul is bronze, then you should be a farmer or laborer or something like that.

18:53.000 --> 19:02.000
And that's a fact about you that identifies you forever and for always, independent of anything you do about it.

19:02.000 --> 19:05.000
And so that's the alternative view.

19:05.000 --> 19:07.000
And you could have modern versions of it.

19:07.000 --> 19:18.000
You could say the thing that identifies you is your IQ or your genetic makeup or the percentage of fast-switch muscle fibers you've got or whatever.

19:18.000 --> 19:26.000
It could be something totally independent of any choice that you've made, independent of the kind of thing about which you could make a choice.

19:26.000 --> 19:29.000
And it categorizes you.

19:29.000 --> 19:31.000
It makes you the person that you are.

19:31.000 --> 19:35.000
That's the thing that Sartre and the existentialists are against.

19:35.000 --> 19:42.000
So this idea that something about you is forever limiting the space of possible decisions you can make.

19:42.000 --> 19:46.000
Sartre says, no, the space is unlimited.

19:46.000 --> 19:49.000
Sartre is the philosopher of radical freedom.

19:49.000 --> 19:50.000
Radical freedom.

19:50.000 --> 19:52.000
Yeah, radical freedom.

19:52.000 --> 20:00.000
And then you could have other existentialists who say, look, we are free, but we got to understand the way in which our freedom is limited by certain things.

20:00.000 --> 20:04.000
We're limited by certain aspects of the kind of being that we are.

20:04.000 --> 20:09.000
If we were radically free, we really would be like God in the traditional medieval sense.

20:09.000 --> 20:18.000
And sort of these folks start with the idea that, look, whatever we are, that's a kind of limit point that we're not going to reach.

20:18.000 --> 20:27.000
So what are the ways in which we're constrained that that being the way the medieval's understood him wasn't constrained?

20:27.000 --> 20:37.000
So can you maybe comment on what is nihilism and is it at all a useful other sort of group of ideas that you resist against in defining existentialism?

20:37.000 --> 20:38.000
Yes, good.

20:38.000 --> 20:39.000
Excellent.

20:39.000 --> 20:46.000
So nihilism, the philosopher who made the term popular, although it was used before him is Nietzsche.

20:46.000 --> 20:53.000
Nietzsche is writing in the end of the 19th century in various places where he published things.

20:53.000 --> 21:03.000
But largely in his unpublished works, he identifies the condition of the modern world as nihilistic.

21:03.000 --> 21:06.000
And that's a descriptive claim.

21:06.000 --> 21:13.000
He's looking around him, trying to figure out what it's like to be us now.

21:13.000 --> 21:23.000
And he says it's a lot different from what it was like to be human in 1300 or in the 5th century BCE.

21:23.000 --> 21:38.000
In 1300, like what people believed, the way they lived their lives was in the understanding that to be human was to be created in the image and likeness of God.

21:38.000 --> 21:40.000
That's the way they understood themselves.

21:40.000 --> 21:47.000
And also to be created sinful because of Adam and Eve's transgression in the Garden of Eden.

21:47.000 --> 21:56.000
And to have the project of trying to understand how as a sinful being, you could nevertheless live a life of virtuous life.

21:56.000 --> 21:57.000
How could you do that?

21:57.000 --> 22:01.000
And it had to do with for them getting in the right relation to God.

22:01.000 --> 22:06.000
Nietzsche says, that doesn't make sense to us anymore in the end of the 19th century.

22:06.000 --> 22:09.000
God is dead, says Nietzsche famously.

22:09.000 --> 22:11.000
And what does that mean?

22:11.000 --> 22:21.000
Well, it means something like the role that God used to play in our understanding of ourselves as a culture isn't a role that God can play anymore.

22:21.000 --> 22:27.000
And so Nietzsche says, the role that God used to play was the role of grounding our existence.

22:27.000 --> 22:31.000
He was what it is in virtue of which we are who we are.

22:31.000 --> 22:38.000
And Nietzsche says, the idea that there is a being that makes us what we are doesn't make sense anymore.

22:38.000 --> 22:41.000
That's like Sartre's atheism, Sartre is taking that from Nietzsche.

22:41.000 --> 22:46.000
And so the question is, what does ground our existence?

22:46.000 --> 22:49.000
And the answer is, nihil, nothing.

22:49.000 --> 22:54.000
And so nihilism is the idea that there's nothing outside of us that grounds our existence.

22:54.000 --> 22:59.000
And then Nietzsche asked the question, well, what are we supposed to do about that?

22:59.000 --> 23:01.000
How do we live?

23:01.000 --> 23:06.000
And I think Nietzsche has a different story than Sartre about that.

23:06.000 --> 23:12.000
Nietzsche doesn't emphasize this notion of radical freedom.

23:12.000 --> 23:14.000
Nietzsche emphasizes something else.

23:14.000 --> 23:18.000
He says, we're artists of life.

23:18.000 --> 23:27.000
And artists are interesting because the natural way of thinking about artists is that they're responding to something.

23:28.000 --> 23:32.000
They find themselves in a situation and they say, this is what's going to make sense of the situation.

23:32.000 --> 23:34.000
This is what I have to write.

23:34.000 --> 23:36.000
This is the way I have to dance.

23:36.000 --> 23:38.000
This is the way I've got to play the music.

23:38.000 --> 23:41.000
And Nietzsche says, we should live like that.

23:41.000 --> 23:49.000
There are constraints, but understanding what they are is a complicated aspect of living itself.

23:50.000 --> 23:57.000
And there's a great story, I think, from music that maybe helps to understand this.

23:57.000 --> 24:01.000
I think Nietzsche, of course, jazz didn't exist when Nietzsche was writing,

24:01.000 --> 24:06.000
but I think Nietzsche really is thinking of something like jazz improvisation.

24:06.000 --> 24:08.000
I mean, he talks about improvisation.

24:08.000 --> 24:09.000
There's classical improvisation.

24:09.000 --> 24:11.000
Nietzsche was, by the way, a musician.

24:11.000 --> 24:14.000
I mean, he was a composer and a pianist.

24:14.000 --> 24:18.000
Not a great one, really, to be fair, but he loved music.

24:18.000 --> 24:27.000
And Herbie Hancock, who's a pianist, a jazz pianist, who played with Miles Davis for quite a while in the 60s,

24:27.000 --> 24:42.000
tells this kind of incredible story that I think exemplifies Nietzsche's view about the way in which we bear some responsibility for being creative.

24:42.000 --> 24:46.000
And that gives us a certain kind of freedom.

24:47.000 --> 24:51.000
But we don't have the radical freedom that starts things.

24:51.000 --> 24:52.000
So what's the story?

24:52.000 --> 25:03.000
Herbie Hancock says, I think they were in Stuttgart, he says, playing a show and things were great, he says.

25:03.000 --> 25:07.000
He's a young pianist and Miles Davis is the master.

25:07.000 --> 25:14.000
And he says, I'm playing the, I'm back in the solo and I'm playing these chords.

25:14.000 --> 25:21.000
And he says, I played this chord and it was the wrong chord.

25:21.000 --> 25:25.000
He's like, it just, like, that's what you got to say.

25:25.000 --> 25:27.000
It didn't work right there.

25:27.000 --> 25:32.000
And I thought, holy mackerel, I screwed up, you know, I screwed up, we were tight, everything was working.

25:32.000 --> 25:35.000
And I blew it for Miles, who's doing his solo.

25:35.000 --> 25:41.000
And he said, Miles paused for a moment.

25:41.000 --> 25:49.000
And then all of a sudden he went on in a way that made my chord right.

25:51.000 --> 26:02.000
And I think that idea that, like, you could be an artist who responds to what's thrown at you in such a way as to make it right.

26:03.000 --> 26:05.000
By what measure?

26:05.000 --> 26:07.000
Everyone could hear it is all you can say.

26:07.000 --> 26:11.000
Everyone knew, wow, that really works.

26:11.000 --> 26:16.000
And I think that's not like, there are constraints, not anything would have worked there.

26:16.000 --> 26:19.000
He couldn't have just played anything.

26:19.000 --> 26:23.000
Most of what anyone would have played would have sounded terrible.

26:23.000 --> 26:26.000
But the constraints aren't like pre-existing.

26:26.000 --> 26:32.000
They're sort of what's happening now in the moment for these listeners and these performers.

26:32.000 --> 26:35.000
And I think that's what Nietzsche thinks the right response to nihilism is.

26:35.000 --> 26:42.000
We're involved, but we're not radically free to make any choice and just stand behind it the way Sartre thinks.

26:42.000 --> 26:45.000
Our choices have to be responsive to our situation.

26:45.000 --> 26:48.000
And they have to make the situation work.

26:48.000 --> 26:50.000
They have to make it right.

26:50.000 --> 26:52.000
And there's something about music, too.

26:52.000 --> 26:57.000
So you basically have to make music of all the moments of life.

26:57.000 --> 26:59.000
And there is something about music.

26:59.000 --> 27:01.000
Why is music so compelling?

27:01.000 --> 27:06.000
And when you listen to it, something about certain kinds of music, it connects with you.

27:06.000 --> 27:07.000
It doesn't make any sense.

27:07.000 --> 27:14.000
But in that same way, for Nietzsche, you should be a creative force that creates a musical masterpiece.

27:14.000 --> 27:15.000
Exactly.

27:15.000 --> 27:20.000
And I think what's interesting is the question, what does it mean to be a creative force there?

27:20.000 --> 27:25.000
There's a traditional notion of creation that we associate with God.

27:25.000 --> 27:30.000
God creates ex nihilo out of nothing.

27:30.000 --> 27:35.000
And you might think that nihilism thinks that we should do that, create ex nihilo,

27:35.000 --> 27:38.000
because it's about how there's nothing at our ground.

27:38.000 --> 27:43.000
But I think the right way to read Nietzsche is to recognize that we don't create out of nothing.

27:43.000 --> 27:45.000
Miles Davis, it wasn't nothing.

27:45.000 --> 27:47.000
That situation pre-existed him.

27:47.000 --> 27:49.000
It was given to him.

27:49.000 --> 27:52.000
Maybe by accident, maybe it was a mistake, whatever.

27:52.000 --> 27:57.000
But he was responding to that situation in a way that made it right.

27:57.000 --> 27:59.000
He wasn't just creating out of nothing.

27:59.000 --> 28:01.000
He was creating out of what was already there.

28:01.000 --> 28:05.000
So that makes that first date with the climbing hand even more complicated.

28:05.000 --> 28:10.000
Because you're given a climbing hand, you're going to have to make art and music out of that.

28:10.000 --> 28:11.000
Exactly.

28:11.000 --> 28:14.000
That's the responsibility for both of them.

28:14.000 --> 28:19.000
Wow, that's a lot of responsibility for his day, because you have to create.

28:19.000 --> 28:22.000
So the emphasis isn't just on making decisions.

28:22.000 --> 28:26.000
It's on creating.

28:26.000 --> 28:28.000
But also on listening, right?

28:28.000 --> 28:31.000
I mean, Miles Davis was listening.

28:31.000 --> 28:32.000
He heard that.

28:32.000 --> 28:33.000
He knew it was wrong.

28:33.000 --> 28:37.000
And the question was, what do I play that makes it right?

28:37.000 --> 28:41.000
So let me ask about Nietzsche, is God dead?

28:41.000 --> 28:43.000
What do you mean by that statement?

28:43.000 --> 28:44.000
Yeah.

28:44.000 --> 28:52.000
What's in your sense the truth behind the question and the possible set of answers that our world today provides?

28:52.000 --> 28:53.000
Good.

28:53.000 --> 29:02.000
So I mean, I think that there's something super perceptive about Nietzsche's diagnosis of the condition at the end of the 19th century.

29:02.000 --> 29:06.000
So not so far from the condition that I think we're currently in.

29:07.000 --> 29:12.000
And I think there's an interesting question, what we're supposed to respond, what we're supposed to do in response.

29:12.000 --> 29:14.000
But what is the condition that we're currently in?

29:14.000 --> 29:28.000
When Nietzsche says God is dead, I think, like I was saying before, he means something like the role that God used to play in grounding our existence is not a role that works for us anymore as a culture.

29:29.000 --> 29:37.000
And when people talk about a view like that nowadays, they use a different terminology, but I think it's roughly what Nietzsche was aiming at.

29:37.000 --> 29:40.000
They say we live in a secular age.

29:40.000 --> 29:42.000
Our age is a secular age.

29:42.000 --> 29:44.000
And so what do people mean when they say that?

29:44.000 --> 29:47.000
I think, first of all, it's a descriptive claim.

29:47.000 --> 29:48.000
It could be wrong.

29:48.000 --> 29:56.000
The question is, does this really describe the way we experience ourselves as a culture or as a culture in the West or wherever it is that we are?

29:57.000 --> 30:01.000
So what does it mean to say that we live in a secular age, an age in which God is dead?

30:01.000 --> 30:05.000
Well, first thing is, it doesn't mean there are no religious believers because there are plenty.

30:05.000 --> 30:11.000
There are lots of people who go to church or synagogue or mosque, you know, every week or more.

30:11.000 --> 30:18.000
And there are people who really find that to be an important aspect of the way they live their lives.

30:19.000 --> 30:32.000
But it does mean that for those people, the role that their religious belief plays in their life isn't the same as it used to be in previous ages.

30:32.000 --> 30:34.000
So what's that role?

30:34.000 --> 30:36.000
We'll go back to the High Middle Ages.

30:36.000 --> 30:38.000
That was clearly not a secular age.

30:38.000 --> 30:40.000
That was a religious age.

30:40.000 --> 30:43.000
And so there we are in 1300.

30:43.000 --> 30:46.000
Dante is writing the Divine Comedy or something.

30:46.000 --> 30:50.000
And what did it mean then to live in a sacred age?

30:50.000 --> 31:10.000
Well, it meant not just that the default was that you were a Christian in the West, but that your Christianity, your religious belief, your religious affiliation justified certain assumptions about people who didn't share that religious belief.

31:11.000 --> 31:26.000
So you're a Christian in the West in 1300 and you meet someone who's a Muslim and the fact that they don't share your religious belief justifies the conclusion that they're less than human.

31:26.000 --> 31:30.000
And that was the ground of the crusades.

31:30.000 --> 31:34.000
That was the religious wars of the High Middle Ages.

31:35.000 --> 31:42.000
To say that we live in a secular age is to say that there aren't a lot of people who have religious belief, there are.

31:42.000 --> 31:48.000
But it's to say that their religious belief doesn't justify that conclusion.

31:48.000 --> 32:02.000
If you're a religious believer and you meet me and suppose I'm not a religious believer, learning that about me doesn't justify your concluding that I'm less than human.

32:02.000 --> 32:05.000
And that's the kind of liberalism of the modern age.

32:05.000 --> 32:08.000
Most of the time we think that's a good thing.

32:08.000 --> 32:10.000
We let a thousand flowers bloom.

32:10.000 --> 32:12.000
There are lots of ways to live a good life.

32:12.000 --> 32:18.000
And there's some way in which that is a nice progressive kind of liberal thought.

32:18.000 --> 32:35.000
But it's also true that it's an undermining thought because it means if you're a religious believer now, your belief can't ground your understanding of what you ought to be aiming at in the life in the way it used to be able to.

32:35.000 --> 32:52.000
You can't say, as a religious believer, I know it's right to do this because you also know that if you meet someone who doesn't share that religious belief and so doesn't think it's right to do that necessarily or does but for different reasons, you can't conclude that they've got it wrong.

32:52.000 --> 32:56.000
So there's this sort of unsettling aspect to it.

32:56.000 --> 33:16.000
Well, isn't it true that you can't conclude as a public statement to others, but within your own mind, it's almost like an existentialist version of belief, which is like you create the world and around you.

33:16.000 --> 33:19.000
It doesn't matter what others believe.

33:19.000 --> 33:33.000
It's actually almost like empowering thought as opposed to the more traditional view of religion where it's like a tribal idea, where you share that idea together.

33:33.000 --> 33:39.000
Here you have the full, back to Sartre, full responsibility of your beliefs as well.

33:39.000 --> 33:40.000
Good, good.

33:40.000 --> 33:44.000
But what you're describing is not a religious believer.

33:44.000 --> 33:51.000
You're describing someone who's found in themselves the ground of their existence rather than in something outside of themselves.

33:52.000 --> 34:10.000
I mean, if you go full Sartrean, then well, you're not in a position to criticize others for the choices that they make, but you are in a position to criticize them for the way in which they make them, either taking responsibility or not taking responsibility.

34:10.000 --> 34:18.000
But the religious believer used to be able to say, look, the choices that I make are right because God demands that I make them.

34:19.000 --> 34:25.000
And nowadays, and so it would be wrong to make any others.

34:25.000 --> 34:34.000
And nowadays, to say that we live in a secular age, say, well, you can't quite do that and be a religious believer.

34:34.000 --> 34:41.000
Your religious belief can't justify that move, and so it can't ground your life in the way it does.

34:41.000 --> 34:42.000
So it's sort of unsettling.

34:42.000 --> 34:47.000
I think that's one of the interpretations of what Nietzsche might have meant when he said God is dead.

34:47.000 --> 34:52.000
God can't play the role for religious believers in our world that he used to.

34:52.000 --> 34:54.000
But we nevertheless find meaning.

34:54.000 --> 35:00.000
I mean, you don't see nihilism as a prevalent set of ideas that are overtaken modern culture.

35:00.000 --> 35:03.000
So a secular world is still full of meaning.

35:03.000 --> 35:04.000
Good.

35:04.000 --> 35:06.000
Well, I think that's the interesting question.

35:06.000 --> 35:14.000
I think it's certainly possible for a secular world to be a world in which we live meaningful lives, worthwhile lives,

35:14.000 --> 35:23.000
lives that are sort of worthy of respect and that we can be proud of aiming to live.

35:23.000 --> 35:27.000
But I think it is a hard question what we're doing when we do that.

35:27.000 --> 35:30.000
And that is the question of existence.

35:30.000 --> 35:36.000
So what does it mean to exist in a way that brings us out at our best as the beings that we are?

35:36.000 --> 35:39.000
That's the question for existentialism.

35:40.000 --> 35:49.000
So besides Sartre, who to you is the most important existentialist to understand for others?

35:49.000 --> 35:52.000
What ideas in particular of theirs do you like?

35:52.000 --> 35:55.000
