36:01.000 --> 36:03.000
Who else is there?

36:03.000 --> 36:10.000
I'm teaching an existentialism course now and I think the tradition goes back at least to the 17th century.

36:10.000 --> 36:14.000
And I'll just tell you some of the figures that I'm teaching there.

36:14.000 --> 36:16.000
We could talk about any of them that you like.

36:16.000 --> 36:19.000
The figure I start with is Pascal.

36:19.000 --> 36:24.000
Pascal, French mathematician from the 17th century.

36:24.000 --> 36:25.000
He died.

36:25.000 --> 36:30.000
I'm terrible with dates, but I think 1661 or something like that, middle of the 17th century.

36:30.000 --> 36:32.000
Brilliant polymath.

36:32.000 --> 36:35.000
Sort of we have computer languages named after him.

36:35.000 --> 36:38.000
He built the first mechanical calculating machine.

36:38.000 --> 36:45.000
But he was also deeply invested in his understanding of what Christianity was.

36:45.000 --> 36:54.000
And he thought that everyone before him had really misunderstood what Christianity was.

36:54.000 --> 37:06.000
That they'd really attempted to think about it, not as a way of living a life, but as a set of beliefs that you can have and which you can justify.

37:06.000 --> 37:12.000
And I think that's the first move that's really pretty interesting.

37:12.000 --> 37:17.000
And then figures like Kierkegaard and Dostoevsky developed that move.

37:17.000 --> 37:27.000
And all of those take themselves to be defending an interpretation of a certain kind of Christianity, an existential interpretation of Christianity.

37:27.000 --> 37:38.000
And then I think there are other figures, other theistic figures, figures like Camus and Fanon, who are mid-20th century figures.

37:38.000 --> 37:43.000
And then I'll just mention the figure who I think is the most interesting is Martin Heidegger.

37:43.000 --> 37:45.000
He's a complicated figure.

37:45.000 --> 37:51.000
By the way, when you said Camus, you meant atheistic.

37:51.000 --> 37:54.000
I think that Camus is an atheistic existentialist.

37:54.000 --> 37:56.000
Yeah, I'm happy to talk about that.

