38:50.000 --> 38:52.000
So I'm super excited about it.

38:52.000 --> 38:55.000
But what is the brother's Karimovsov about?

38:55.000 --> 38:58.000
I mean, without spoiling the ending for anyone.

38:58.000 --> 38:59.000
Spoiler alert.

38:59.000 --> 39:00.000
Yeah.

39:00.000 --> 39:03.000
I mean, look, it's a murder mystery, right?

39:03.000 --> 39:06.000
I mean, the father gets murdered.

39:06.000 --> 39:08.000
And the question is who did it?

39:08.000 --> 39:09.000
Who's responsible for it?

39:09.000 --> 39:12.000
So there's a notion of responsibility here, like in Sartre.

39:12.000 --> 39:15.000
But it's responsibility for a murder.

39:15.000 --> 39:17.000
That's what we're talking about.

39:17.000 --> 39:24.000
And there's a bunch of brothers, each of whom has pretty good motivation

39:24.000 --> 39:26.000
for having murdered the father.

39:26.000 --> 39:28.000
The father's a jerk.

39:28.000 --> 39:33.000
I mean, he's, you know, if anybody is worthy of being murdered, he's the guy.

39:33.000 --> 39:36.000
He's a force of chaos.

39:36.000 --> 39:39.000
And he's nasty in all sorts of ways.

39:39.000 --> 39:43.000
But still, it's not good to murder people.

39:43.000 --> 39:46.000
So what's the view of Dostoyevsky?

39:46.000 --> 39:54.000
I mean, it's this intense exploration of what it means to be involved in various ways

39:54.000 --> 39:59.000
with an activity that everyone can recognize as atrocious.

39:59.000 --> 40:05.000
And what the right way is to take responsibility for that?

40:05.000 --> 40:10.000
What the right way is to relate to others in the face of it?

40:10.000 --> 40:16.000
And how even through this kind of action, you can achieve some kind of salvation?

40:16.000 --> 40:19.000
That's Dostoyevsky's word for it.

40:19.000 --> 40:24.000
You can, but salvation here and now, not like you live some afterlife

40:24.000 --> 40:27.000
where you're, you know, paradise for eternity.

40:27.000 --> 40:29.000
Who cares about that?

40:29.000 --> 40:31.000
Says one of the characters.

40:31.000 --> 40:33.000
That doesn't make my life now any good.

40:33.000 --> 40:37.000
And it doesn't justify any of the bad things that happen in my life now.

40:37.000 --> 40:42.000
What matters is, can we live well in the face of these things that we do

40:42.000 --> 40:44.000
and have to take responsibility for?

40:44.000 --> 40:50.000
So it's this intense exploration of notions and gradations of guilt

40:50.000 --> 40:56.000
and responsibility and the possibility of love and salvation in the face of those.

40:56.000 --> 40:59.000
It is incredibly human work.

40:59.000 --> 41:03.000
But I think Dostoyevsky is the opposite of Sartre.

41:03.000 --> 41:06.000
And let me just, I think it's so fascinating.

41:06.000 --> 41:12.000
I don't know anybody else who notices this, but Sartre actually quotes a passage from Dostoyevsky

41:12.000 --> 41:14.000
when he's developing his view.

41:14.000 --> 41:16.000
It's close to a passage.

41:16.000 --> 41:18.000
It doesn't appear quite in this way.

41:18.000 --> 41:21.000
But the passage that Sartre quotes is this.

41:21.000 --> 41:23.000
It's in the form of an argument.

41:23.000 --> 41:25.000
Sartre puts it in the form of an argument.

41:25.000 --> 41:29.000
He says, look, there's a conditional statement is true.

41:29.000 --> 41:33.000
If there is no God, then everything is permitted.

41:33.000 --> 41:36.000
And then there's a second premise.

41:36.000 --> 41:38.000
There is no God.

41:38.000 --> 41:39.000
That's Sartre's view.

41:39.000 --> 41:40.000
I mean, he's an atheist.

41:40.000 --> 41:41.000
There is no God.

41:41.000 --> 41:43.000
Conclusion?

41:43.000 --> 41:45.000
Everything is permitted.

41:45.000 --> 41:47.000
And that's Sartre's radical freedom.

41:47.000 --> 41:51.000
And if you think about the structure of the brothers Karamazov,

41:51.000 --> 41:54.000
I think Dostoyevsky, though he never says it this way,

41:54.000 --> 41:56.000
would run the argument differently.

41:56.000 --> 41:59.000
It's a modus tolens instead of a modus bonens.

41:59.000 --> 42:02.000
The argument for Dostoyevsky would go like this.

42:02.000 --> 42:04.000
Yeah, conditional statement.

42:04.000 --> 42:07.000
If there is no God, then everything is permitted.

42:07.000 --> 42:09.000
But look at your life.

42:09.000 --> 42:11.000
Not everything is permitted.

42:11.000 --> 42:14.000
You do horrible, atrocious things.

42:14.000 --> 42:17.000
Like, be involved in the death of your father.

42:17.000 --> 42:19.000
And there is a price to pay.

42:19.000 --> 42:25.000
That's not a livable moment to take, to have to take responsibility,

42:25.000 --> 42:29.000
to have to recognize that you're at fault,

42:29.000 --> 42:34.000
or you're somehow guilty for having been involved in whatever way you were

42:34.000 --> 42:37.000
and letting that happen or bringing it about that it does happen,

42:37.000 --> 42:39.000
is to pay a price.

42:39.000 --> 42:44.000
So we're not beings that are constituted in such a way that everything is permitted.

42:44.000 --> 42:47.000
Look at the facts of your existence.

42:47.000 --> 42:49.000
So not everything is permitted.

42:49.000 --> 42:54.000
Therefore, there is a God.

42:54.000 --> 42:59.000
And the presence of a God for Dostoyevsky, I think, is just found

42:59.000 --> 43:03.000
in this fact that when we do bad things, we feel guilty for them.

43:03.000 --> 43:06.000
We find ourselves to be responsible for things,

43:06.000 --> 43:08.000
even when we didn't intend to do them,

43:08.000 --> 43:10.000
but we just allowed ourselves to be involved in them.

43:10.000 --> 43:14.000
And the nature of God for Dostoyevsky is, I mean, unclear.

43:14.000 --> 43:17.000
I mean, it's a very complex exploration in itself.

43:17.000 --> 43:22.000
And he basically, God speaks through several of his characters in complicated ways.

43:22.000 --> 43:26.000
So it's not like a trivial version of God.

43:26.000 --> 43:27.000
It's totally not trivial.

43:27.000 --> 43:31.000
And it's not a being that exists outside of time.

43:31.000 --> 43:33.000
None of that is sort of relevant for Dostoyevsky.

43:33.000 --> 43:36.000
For him, it's a question about how we live our lives.

43:36.000 --> 43:40.000
Do we live our lives in the mood that Christianity says it makes available to us,

43:40.000 --> 43:42.000
which is the mood of joy?

