It's understanding something much deeper.

46:47.000 --> 46:50.000
The music of the language or something.

46:50.000 --> 46:52.000
The music of the ideas.

46:52.000 --> 46:54.000
Absolutely. Something like that.

46:54.000 --> 46:56.000
It's very hard to say exactly what that is.

46:56.000 --> 47:01.000
But when you hear an Irish person who really understands Joyce, read some sentences.

47:01.000 --> 47:03.000
They have a different cadence.

47:03.000 --> 47:05.000
They have a different tonality.

47:05.000 --> 47:07.000
They have different music to use your word.

47:07.000 --> 47:10.000
And all of a sudden you think about them differently.

47:10.000 --> 47:15.000
And the sentences sort of draw different thoughts out of you when they're read in certain ways.

47:15.000 --> 47:18.000
That's what great actors can do.

47:18.000 --> 47:22.000
But I think language is rich like that.

47:22.000 --> 47:30.000
And the idea which philosophers tend to have that we're really studying the crucial aspects of language

47:30.000 --> 47:33.000
when we think about its logical form.

47:33.000 --> 47:37.000
When we think about the sort of claims of philosophical logic that you can make

47:37.000 --> 47:41.000
or how do you translate this proposition into some symbolic form.

47:41.000 --> 47:44.000
I think that's part of what goes on in language.

47:44.000 --> 47:50.000
But I think that when language affects us in the deep way that it can

47:50.000 --> 47:57.000
when great poets or great writers or great thinkers use it to great effect

47:57.000 --> 47:58.000
it's way more than that.

47:58.000 --> 48:01.000
And that's the interesting form of language that I'm interested in.

48:01.000 --> 48:04.000
It's kind of a challenge I'm hoping to take on is

48:04.000 --> 48:09.000
I feel like some of the ideas that are conveyed through language

48:09.000 --> 48:11.000
actually can be put outside of language.

48:11.000 --> 48:17.000
So one of the challenges I have to do is to have a conversation with people in Russian

48:17.000 --> 48:22.000
but for an English audience and not rely purely on translators.

48:22.000 --> 48:29.000
There would of course be translators there that help me dance through this mess of language.

48:29.000 --> 48:35.000
But also like my goal, my hope is to dance from Russian to English back and forth

48:35.000 --> 48:39.000
for an English speaking audience and for a Russian speaking audience.

48:39.000 --> 48:43.000
So not this pure, this is Russian, it's going to be translated to English

48:43.000 --> 48:46.000
or this is English, it's going to be translated to Russian.

48:46.000 --> 48:52.000
But dance back and forth and try to share with people who don't speak one of the languages

48:52.000 --> 48:56.000
the music that they're missing and sort of almost hear that music

48:56.000 --> 49:00.000
because if you're sitting in another room and you hear the music through the wall

49:00.000 --> 49:01.000
I get a sense of it.

49:01.000 --> 49:08.000
I think that would be a waste if I don't try to pursue this being a bilingual human being.

49:08.000 --> 49:14.000
And I wonder whether it's possible to capture some of the magic of the ideas

49:14.000 --> 49:19.000
in a way that can be conveyed to people who don't speak that particular language.

49:19.000 --> 49:21.000
I think it's a super exciting project.

49:21.000 --> 49:23.000
I look forward to following it.

49:23.000 --> 49:25.000
I'll tell you one thing that does happen.

49:25.000 --> 49:27.000
So we read Dostoevsky in translation.

49:27.000 --> 49:31.000
Occasionally I do have Russian speakers in the room which is super helpful.

49:31.000 --> 49:39.000
But I also encourage my students to some of them will have different translations than others.

49:39.000 --> 49:43.000
And that can be really helpful for the non-native speaker

49:43.000 --> 49:51.000
because by paying attention to the places where translators diverge in their translations

49:51.000 --> 49:53.000
of a given word or a phrase or something like that

49:53.000 --> 49:58.000
you can start to get the idea that somehow the words that we have in English

49:58.000 --> 50:03.000
they don't have the same contours as the word in Russian that's being translated.

50:03.000 --> 50:07.000
And then you can start to ask about what those differences are.

50:07.000 --> 50:11.000
And I think there's a kind of magic to it.

50:11.000 --> 50:16.000
I mean, it's astonishing how rich and affecting these languages can be

50:16.000 --> 50:20.000
for people who really grew up in them especially who speak them as natives.

50:20.000 --> 50:24.000
And that's a really powerful thing that actually doesn't exist enough of

50:24.000 --> 50:33.000
is, for example, for Dostoevsky most novels have been translated by two or three famous translators.

50:33.000 --> 50:37.000
And there's a lot of discussions about who did it better and so on.

50:37.000 --> 50:42.000
But I would love to, I'm a computer science person, I would love to do a diff

50:42.000 --> 50:48.000
where you automatically detect all the differences in the translation just as you're saying

50:48.000 --> 50:56.000
and use that like somebody needs to publish literally just books describing the differences.

50:56.000 --> 50:58.000
In fact, I'll probably do a little bit of this.

50:58.000 --> 51:02.000
I heard the individual translators and interviews and blog posts

51:02.000 --> 51:06.000
and articles discuss particular phrases that they differ on

51:06.000 --> 51:10.000
but like to do that for an entire book, that's a fascinating exploration.

51:10.000 --> 51:15.000
As an English speaker, just to read the differences in the translations

51:15.000 --> 51:22.000
you probably can get some deep understanding of ideas in those books

51:22.000 --> 51:26.000
by seeing the struggle of the translators to capture that idea.

51:26.000 --> 51:28.000
That's a really interesting idea.

51:28.000 --> 51:29.000
Absolutely.

51:29.000 --> 51:33.000
And you can do that for other projects and other languages too.

51:33.000 --> 51:38.000
One of the, I don't know, I have this weird huge range of interests

51:38.000 --> 51:41.000
and some days I'll find myself reading about something.

51:41.000 --> 51:46.000
At one point I was interested in 14th century German mysticism.

51:46.000 --> 51:50.000
Okay, turns out there's somebody who's written volumes and volumes about this.

51:50.000 --> 51:52.000
He's fantastic.

51:52.000 --> 51:55.000
And I was interested in reading Meister Eckhart.

51:55.000 --> 51:58.000
I wanted to know what was interesting about him.

51:58.000 --> 52:05.000
And the sort of move that this guy Bernard McGinn, who's the great scholar of this period, made

52:05.000 --> 52:10.000
was to say what Eckhart did, and everybody knows this,

52:10.000 --> 52:13.000
he translated Christianity into the vernacular.

52:13.000 --> 52:16.000
He started giving sermons in German to the peasants.

52:16.000 --> 52:18.000
Sermons used to be in Latin and nobody could speak Latin.

52:18.000 --> 52:22.000
Can you imagine sitting there for a two hour sermon in a language that you don't know?

52:22.000 --> 52:25.000
So he translated it into German.

52:25.000 --> 52:29.000
But in doing it, the resources of the German language are different from the resources

52:29.000 --> 52:30.000
of the Latin language.

52:30.000 --> 52:37.000
And there's a word in Middle High German, Grund, which we translated as ground.

52:38.000 --> 52:41.000
And it's got this earthy feel to it.

52:41.000 --> 52:47.000
It sort of invokes the notion of soil and what you stand on and what things grow out of

52:47.000 --> 52:54.000
and sort of what you could run your fingers through that would have a kind of honesty to it.

52:54.000 --> 52:57.000
And there's no Latin word for that.

52:57.000 --> 53:02.000
But in Eckhart's interpretation of Christianity, Grund, that's like the fundamental thing.

53:02.000 --> 53:06.000
You don't understand God until you understand the way in which he is our ground.

53:06.000 --> 53:15.000
And all of a sudden, this mysticism gets a kind of German cant that makes sense to the people who speak German

53:15.000 --> 53:23.000
and that reveals something totally different about what you could think that form of existence was

53:23.000 --> 53:26.000
that was covered over by the fact that it had always been done in Latin.

53:27.000 --> 53:29.000
Yeah, that's fascinating.

53:29.000 --> 53:36.000
So, okay, we talked about Dostoyevsky and the use of murder to explore human nature.

53:36.000 --> 53:44.000
Let's go to Camus, who is maybe less concerned with murder, more concerned with suicide as a way to explore human nature.

53:44.000 --> 53:52.000
So he is probably my favorite existentialist, probably one of the more accessible existentialists.

53:52.000 --> 53:58.000
And like you said, one of the people who didn't like to call himself an existentialist.

53:58.000 --> 54:00.000
So what are your thoughts about Camus?

54:00.000 --> 54:03.000
What role does he play in the story of existentialism?

54:03.000 --> 54:06.000
So, I find Camus totally fascinating.

54:06.000 --> 54:07.000
I really do.

54:07.000 --> 54:15.000
And for years, I didn't teach Camus because the famous thing that you're referring to, the myth of Sisyphus,

54:15.000 --> 54:20.000
which is a sort of essay, it's published as a book, super accessible, really fascinating.

54:20.000 --> 54:23.000
He's a great writer, really engaging.

54:23.000 --> 54:31.000
The opening line is something like, there is but one truly significant philosophical question.

54:31.000 --> 54:33.000
And that is the question of suicide.

54:33.000 --> 54:38.000
And I thought, I can't teach my 18-year-olds of, you know, like how...

54:38.000 --> 54:39.000
Yeah.

54:39.000 --> 54:41.000
I just thought, that's terrible.

54:41.000 --> 54:42.000
Like, how can I...

54:42.000 --> 54:44.000
I mean, it's not wrong.

54:44.000 --> 54:45.000
Like, that's a...

54:45.000 --> 54:47.000
But do I want to bring that into the classroom?

54:47.000 --> 54:49.000
And so I read it...

54:49.000 --> 54:51.000
I read the essay.

54:51.000 --> 54:53.000
I avoided it for a long time because...

54:53.000 --> 54:55.000
Just because of that line.

54:55.000 --> 55:00.000
And I thought, I'm not going to be able to make sense of this in a way that will be helpful for anyone.

55:00.000 --> 55:04.000
But finally, one year, maybe seven or eight years ago, I sat down to read it.

55:04.000 --> 55:07.000
I thought, I've got to really confront it.

55:07.000 --> 55:11.000
And I read it and it's incredibly engaging.

55:11.000 --> 55:13.000
I mean, it's really, really beautiful.

55:13.000 --> 55:17.000
And Camus was against suicide, which just turns out to be good.

55:17.000 --> 55:19.000
I was happy about that.

55:19.000 --> 55:26.000
But he has a bit of a bleak understanding of what human existence amounts to.

55:26.000 --> 55:32.000
And so in the end, he thinks that human existence is absurd.

55:32.000 --> 55:36.000
And it's being absurd as a kind of technical term for him.

55:36.000 --> 55:48.000
And it means that the episodes in your life and your life as a whole presents itself to you as if it's got a meaning.

55:49.000 --> 55:51.000
But really it doesn't.

55:51.000 --> 55:58.000
So there's this tension between the way things seem to be on their surface

55:58.000 --> 56:03.000
and what really turns out to be true about them.

56:03.000 --> 56:05.000
And he gives these great examples.

56:05.000 --> 56:07.000
You probably remember these.

56:07.000 --> 56:09.000
He says, there you are.

56:09.000 --> 56:14.000
You're walking along the street and there's a plate glass window in a building.

56:14.000 --> 56:18.000
And through the window, you see somebody talking on a cell phone.

56:18.000 --> 56:22.000
I mean, I imagine it as a cell phone, but Camus for didn't.

56:22.000 --> 56:26.000
But you see somebody talking on a cell phone and he's animated.

56:26.000 --> 56:31.000
He's talking a lot as if things really meant something.

56:31.000 --> 56:35.000
And yet Camus says, it's a dumb show.

56:35.000 --> 56:39.000
And it's not dumb in the sense, just in the sense that it's stupid.

56:39.000 --> 56:41.000
It's dumb in the sense that it's silent.

56:41.000 --> 56:47.000
It presents itself as if it's got some significance and yet its significance is withheld from you.

56:47.000 --> 56:49.000
And he says, that's what our lives are like.

56:49.000 --> 56:54.000
Everything in our lives presents themselves to us as if it's got a significance, but it doesn't.

56:54.000 --> 56:56.000
It's absurd.

56:56.000 --> 56:59.000
And then he says, really what our lives are like?

56:59.000 --> 57:01.000
They're like the lives of Sisyphus.

57:01.000 --> 57:04.000
Just day after day.

57:04.000 --> 57:07.000
You do the same thing.

57:07.000 --> 57:09.000
You wake up at a certain time.

57:09.000 --> 57:10.000
You get on the bus.

57:10.000 --> 57:11.000
You go to work.

57:11.000 --> 57:12.000
You take your lunch break.

57:12.000 --> 57:13.000
You get off.

57:13.000 --> 57:17.000
I have a colleague who once said to me something like this.

57:17.000 --> 57:20.000
It was about October or so in the fall semester.

57:20.000 --> 57:22.000
I said, how's it going, Dick?

57:22.000 --> 57:24.000
He said, well, you know how it is.

57:24.000 --> 57:29.000
I got on the conveyor belt at the beginning of the semester and I'm just going through.

57:29.000 --> 57:32.000
And that's the way my life is.

57:32.000 --> 57:39.000
And Camus thinks that experience, which you can sometimes have, reveals something true

57:39.000 --> 57:41.000
about what human lives are like.

57:41.000 --> 57:46.000
Our lives really just are like the life of Sisyphus who rolls this boulder up the hill

57:46.000 --> 57:48.000
from morning till night.

57:48.000 --> 57:53.000
And then at night he gets to the top and it rolls back down to the bottom.

57:53.000 --> 57:57.000
Over the course of the night he walks back down and then he starts it all over again.

57:57.000 --> 58:00.000
And he says, Sisyphus is condemned to this life.

58:00.000 --> 58:07.000
Like we're condemned to our lives, but we do have one bit of freedom and it's the only

58:07.000 --> 58:10.000
thing that we can hang on to.

58:10.000 --> 58:18.000
It's the freedom to stick it to the gods who put us in this position by embracing this

58:18.000 --> 58:21.000
existence rather than giving up and committing suicide.

58:21.000 --> 58:26.000
And I thought, well, it's kind of a happy ending.

58:27.000 --> 58:33.000
But I also thought it's a dim view of what our existence amounts to.

58:33.000 --> 58:37.000
So I think there's something fascinating about that.

58:37.000 --> 58:43.000
But what I came to believe and I tried to write about this once, I know you read the thing

58:43.000 --> 58:46.000
about a liveness that I published once.

58:46.000 --> 58:48.000
That's secretly a criticism of Camus.

58:48.000 --> 58:50.000
I don't think I mentioned Camus in there.

58:50.000 --> 58:56.000
But I think Camus has got the phenomenon wrong or he's missed some important aspect of it.

58:56.000 --> 59:03.000
Because in Camus' view, when you experience your day as sort of going on in this deadening way

59:03.000 --> 59:07.000
and you're just doing the things that you always do, the way you always do them.

59:07.000 --> 59:11.000
For Camus, that reveals the truth about what our lives are.

59:11.000 --> 59:14.000
But I think there's some aspect, at least for me.

59:14.000 --> 59:19.000
And maybe he just didn't feel this or didn't have access to it.

59:19.000 --> 59:20.000
Maybe others don't.

59:20.000 --> 59:27.000
But for me, there's an extra part to it, which is somehow that, yes, that's the way things are.

59:27.000 --> 59:30.000
And it's inadequate.

59:30.000 --> 59:37.000
And there's something that's missing from that aspect of our existence that could be there.

59:37.000 --> 59:45.000
And it feels like our lives are not about just putting up with that and sticking it to the gods by embracing it.

59:45.000 --> 59:48.000
But seeking that absent part of it.

59:48.000 --> 59:54.000
The part that's recognizable in its absence in your experience of that.

59:54.000 --> 59:56.000
And that's what I think.

59:56.000 --> 01:00:04.000
I think we do have the experience of the presence of that in moments when you feel truly alive.

01:00:04.000 --> 01:00:08.000
And that's what you mean by the word aliveness, which is a fascinating and a powerful word.

01:00:08.000 --> 01:00:10.000
Yeah, that's what I mean by it.

01:00:10.000 --> 01:00:17.000
I mean, I think most people can recognize moments in their lives when they really felt alive.

01:00:17.000 --> 01:00:26.000
And it could happen in a moment when, I don't know, maybe Miles Davis felt it in that moment when he was responding to Herbie Hancock's chord.

01:00:26.000 --> 01:00:34.000
Or maybe you feel it in that moment where you grab for the hand on the first date and the gesture is reciprocated.

01:00:34.000 --> 01:00:45.000
Or maybe you feel it in some moment when you are doing a kind of peak athletic thing or watching somebody else do a peak athletic thing.

01:00:45.000 --> 01:00:54.000
But I think there are moments when it feels like it's not like the way Camu is describing things.

01:00:54.000 --> 01:00:56.000
And it's better because of that.

01:00:56.000 --> 01:01:07.000
So I think one really powerful way for me to understand aliveness is to think about going to a darker territory, is to think about suicide.

01:01:07.000 --> 01:01:12.000
And I've known people in my life who suffer from clinical depression.

01:01:12.000 --> 01:01:23.000
And, you know, whatever the chemistry is in our brain, there is a certain kind of feeling that is to be depressed.

01:01:23.000 --> 01:01:30.000
Where you look in the mirror and ask, do I want to kill myself today?

01:01:30.000 --> 01:01:36.000
This is the question that Camu asks, this question, this philosophical question.

01:01:36.000 --> 01:01:48.000
And there is people who, when they're depressed, say, not only do they say, I want to kill myself or I don't, they say, it doesn't matter.

01:01:48.000 --> 01:01:54.000
And that's chemistry, that's whatever that is, that's chemistry in our mind.

01:01:54.000 --> 01:02:03.000
And then on the flip side of that, for me, I've had some low points, but I've been very fortunate to not suffer from that kind of depression.

01:02:03.000 --> 01:02:13.000
I am the opposite, which is not only moments of peak performance in athletics or great music or any of that.

01:02:13.000 --> 01:02:18.000
I'm just deeply joyful often by mundane things.

01:02:18.000 --> 01:02:22.000
Like, as you were saying it, I was drinking this thing and it's cold.

01:02:22.000 --> 01:02:28.000
And for some reason, the coldness of that was like, oh, great, like refrigeration.

01:02:28.000 --> 01:02:30.000
I don't know, there was a joy in that.

01:02:30.000 --> 01:02:33.000
I can't put it into words, but I just felt great.

01:02:33.000 --> 01:02:40.000
And then just so many things, you look out in nature, there's a nice breeze and it's amazing.

01:02:40.000 --> 01:02:46.000
So that doesn't feel like I'm embracing the absurd.

01:02:46.000 --> 01:02:54.000
That seems like I'm getting some nice dopamine hits in whatever the chemistry is from just the basics of life.

01:02:54.000 --> 01:02:56.000
And that is the source of aliveness.

01:02:56.000 --> 01:03:05.000
However my brain is built, it's gotten a natural sort of mechanism for aliveness.

01:03:05.000 --> 01:03:14.000
And so the one nice way to see the absence of aliveness is to look at the chemical, the clinical depression.

01:03:14.000 --> 01:03:20.000
And so that Camus doesn't seem to contend with that at all in asking the question of suicide.

01:03:20.000 --> 01:03:25.000
Because when you look in the mirror and ask, like, if I ask myself, do I want to kill myself today?

01:03:25.000 --> 01:03:29.000
I ask that question in a different way, more like a stoic way often.

01:03:29.000 --> 01:03:33.000
Like basically every day is, you know, what if I die today?

01:03:33.000 --> 01:03:37.000
It's more like contemplating your mortality every single day.

01:03:37.000 --> 01:03:44.000
You know, that excites me, the possibility that this is my last day.

01:03:44.000 --> 01:03:47.000
You know, it just reminds me how amazing life is.

01:03:47.000 --> 01:03:57.000
And that's chemistry. I don't know what that is, but that's certainly not some kind of philosophical decision I made.

01:03:57.000 --> 01:04:04.000
I am a little bit riding a wave of the chemistry of the genetics I've been given of the dopamine.

01:04:04.000 --> 01:04:07.000
So that question of suicide.

01:04:07.000 --> 01:04:14.000
By the way, do you find that formulation of the question of existentialism?

01:04:14.000 --> 01:04:20.000
I know you didn't want to teach it because obviously suicide is a very difficult word, especially for young minds.

01:04:20.000 --> 01:04:25.000
But do you think that's a useful formulation of the question of existentialism?

01:04:25.000 --> 01:04:29.000
Like him saying, this is the most important question of suicide.

01:04:29.000 --> 01:04:31.000
I think there is something to it.

01:04:31.000 --> 01:04:42.000
If you read the question as the question, what is it in virtue of which it ought to be desirable to live the lives that we're capable of living?

01:04:42.000 --> 01:04:44.000
That's a deep question.

01:04:44.000 --> 01:04:52.000
Yeah, that's a question that gets focused when someone asks themselves whether they ought to continue to live that life.

01:04:52.000 --> 01:04:59.000
The famous line, nothing focuses the mind more than one's impending execution.

01:04:59.000 --> 01:05:10.000
I think there's something important about that, that recognizing the riskiness and the vulnerability of one's existence

01:05:10.000 --> 01:05:12.000
is super important.

01:05:12.000 --> 01:05:20.000
And I think that if we didn't have that, our lives wouldn't be capable of being meaningful.

01:05:20.000 --> 01:05:24.000
If they weren't risky and vulnerable, there would be nothing to lose.

01:05:24.000 --> 01:05:29.000
And it's only because there are things to lose that they can come to have the significance that they do.

01:05:29.000 --> 01:05:37.000
So yeah, I think not against the idea that that's a deep way of approaching the questions at the core of existentialism.

01:05:38.000 --> 01:05:43.000
But as you said, I was worried for a while about how I was going to teach it.

01:05:43.000 --> 01:05:50.000
Well, I think there's a difference between suicide and not living because suicide is an action.

01:05:50.000 --> 01:06:03.000
So it feels like to me, like suicide doesn't make sense because you know, imagine you're in like a hotel and you're saying the room I'm in sucks.

01:06:03.000 --> 01:06:12.000
But like there's other rooms, so like maybe explore those other rooms, maybe you'll find meaning in those other rooms.

01:06:12.000 --> 01:06:20.000
Like basically embracing the fact that you don't know everything and there's, you need time to explore everything.

01:06:20.000 --> 01:06:30.000
It's like once you've explored everything, then maybe you can make a full decision, but it's unfair to make a decision.

01:06:30.000 --> 01:06:36.000
It's, I would say, unethical to make a decision until you've explored all the rooms in the hotel.

01:06:36.000 --> 01:06:40.000
Yeah. And this gets focused in the brothers Karamazov, of course.

01:06:40.000 --> 01:06:47.000
There's one brother who is really asking that question, is asking the question of suicide.

01:06:47.000 --> 01:06:54.000
He's asking the question whether the world that we live in is a world that's worth living in.

01:06:54.000 --> 01:06:59.000
And I think that character is, as you say, very ill.

01:06:59.000 --> 01:07:08.000
And it's possible and often because, as you say, of, you know, brain chemistry, physiology.

01:07:08.000 --> 01:07:15.000
So there's certainly a physical ground to that situation, to that condition.

01:07:15.000 --> 01:07:20.000
But I think it is possible for someone to be in that situation.

01:07:20.000 --> 01:07:31.000
I think that Ivan Karamazov, who's the character who's asking this question, is, you know, maybe let's say chemically depressed or something like that.

01:07:31.000 --> 01:07:33.000
But I think there's more to it too.

