I think, so one thing to say is that the nihilists, the group of nihilists who call themselves nihilists,

01:14:57.000 --> 01:15:03.000
I think they've got a bad misinterpretation of what nihilism is supposed to be.

01:15:03.000 --> 01:15:07.000
And this happened actually in the 20s.

01:15:07.000 --> 01:15:16.000
There was a famous case of a couple of German students, Leopold and Loeb, who'd read a lot of Nietzsche.

01:15:16.000 --> 01:15:26.000
Nietzsche, you know, was a kind of hero for the Nazis even, I think based on a pretty bad misunderstanding of what he was up to.

01:15:26.000 --> 01:15:31.000
But Leopold and Loeb had the bad understanding first and they were students.

01:15:31.000 --> 01:15:35.000
They'd read a lot of Nietzsche and they thought, okay, nothing means anything.

01:15:35.000 --> 01:15:44.000
The only way that there's any significance in life is through our will to sort of powerfully bring something about.

01:15:44.000 --> 01:15:58.000
And if we're going to do that in a way that reflects the fact that nothing means anything, then what we should do is take these things, these actions that people always thought were bad,

01:15:58.000 --> 01:16:02.000
and do them and show that there's nothing wrong with doing them.

01:16:02.000 --> 01:16:09.000
And so they decided they would murder someone, not because they were angry at them, just someone they'd never met.

01:16:09.000 --> 01:16:11.000
It was important that it was someone they'd never met.

01:16:11.000 --> 01:16:13.000
It was a totally unmotivated act.

01:16:13.000 --> 01:16:29.000
And they thought, we'll embrace nihilism by showing that we can act in such a way as to do something that morality thinks is bad and through our will bring it about that we desire to do it.

01:16:29.000 --> 01:16:34.000
For no reason that has anything to do with its potentially being interpretable as good.

01:16:34.000 --> 01:16:41.000
And I think that's a terrible misreading of what Nietzsche thinks the response to nihilism is.

01:16:41.000 --> 01:16:44.000
I mean, I think read that against the Miles Davis thing.

01:16:44.000 --> 01:16:53.000
Miles Davis' aim is to creatively bring it about that something works well in a situation where he is kind of constrained.

01:16:53.000 --> 01:16:54.000
So they thought two things.

01:16:54.000 --> 01:17:01.000
One, there are no constraints at all, not even the constraints of the situation that we find ourselves in.

01:17:01.000 --> 01:17:10.000
And two, we only become the beings that we really are when we act against what you might have thought the constraints were.

01:17:10.000 --> 01:17:14.000
And I just think that's a bad misreading of what that kind of nihilism is up to.

01:17:14.000 --> 01:17:20.000
And I think maybe that group in the Big Lebowski has got that kind of bad misreading.

