I mean, the big picture is that Heidegger thinks,

01:40:58.000 --> 01:41:01.000
and he's not really wrong to think this,

01:41:01.000 --> 01:41:06.000
that the whole history of philosophy from Plato forward,

01:41:06.000 --> 01:41:08.000
maybe even from the pre-Socratics forward,

01:41:08.000 --> 01:41:13.000
from like the sixth century BC to now,

01:41:13.000 --> 01:41:16.000
has been motivated by a certain kind,

01:41:16.000 --> 01:41:19.000
or has been grounded on a certain kind of assumption

01:41:19.000 --> 01:41:22.000
that it didn't have the right to make,

01:41:22.000 --> 01:41:24.000
and that it's led us astray,

01:41:24.000 --> 01:41:29.000
and that until we understand the way in which it's led us astray,

01:41:29.000 --> 01:41:34.000
we're not going to be able to get to grips with the condition we now find ourselves in.

01:41:34.000 --> 01:41:39.000
So let me start with what he thinks the condition we now find ourselves in is.

01:41:39.000 --> 01:41:42.000
Lots of periods to Heidegger's views.

01:41:42.000 --> 01:41:46.000
I'm just going to sort of mush it all together for the purposes of today.

01:41:46.000 --> 01:41:51.000
Heidegger thinks that one of the crucial things that we need to contend with

01:41:51.000 --> 01:41:56.000
when we think about what it is to be us now

01:41:56.000 --> 01:42:01.000
is that the right name for our age is a technological age.

01:42:01.000 --> 01:42:05.000
Now, what does it mean for our age to be a technological age?

01:42:05.000 --> 01:42:14.000
Well, it means that we have an understanding of what it is for anything at all to be at all,

01:42:14.000 --> 01:42:20.000
that we never really chose that sort of animating the way we live our lives,

01:42:20.000 --> 01:42:24.000
that's animating our understanding of ourselves and everything else,

01:42:24.000 --> 01:42:27.000
that is quite limited,

01:42:27.000 --> 01:42:32.000
organized around the idea that to be something

01:42:32.000 --> 01:42:41.000
is to be what's sitting there as an infinitely flexible reserve

01:42:41.000 --> 01:42:45.000
to be optimized and made efficient.

01:42:45.000 --> 01:42:55.000
And Heidegger thinks that that's not just the way we think of silicon circuits,

01:42:55.000 --> 01:43:00.000
or the river when we put a hydroelectric power plant on it,

01:43:00.000 --> 01:43:05.000
we're optimizing the flow of the river so that it makes energy which is infinitely flexible

01:43:05.000 --> 01:43:07.000
and we can use it in any way at all.

01:43:07.000 --> 01:43:11.000
It's the way we understand ourselves, too.

01:43:11.000 --> 01:43:19.000
We think of ourselves as this reserve of potential that needs to be made efficient and optimized.

01:43:19.000 --> 01:43:24.000
And when I talk with my students about it, I ask them,

01:43:24.000 --> 01:43:27.000
like, what's your calendar look like?

01:43:27.000 --> 01:43:30.000
What's the goal of your day?

01:43:30.000 --> 01:43:33.000
Is it to get as many things into it as possible?

01:43:33.000 --> 01:43:40.000
Is it to feel like I've failed unless I've made my life so efficient

01:43:40.000 --> 01:43:43.000
that I'm doing this and this and this and this and this,

01:43:43.000 --> 01:43:45.000
that I can't let things go by?

01:43:45.000 --> 01:43:52.000
The feeling that I think we all have that there's some pressure to do that,

01:43:52.000 --> 01:44:00.000
to relate to ourselves that way is a clue to what Heidegger thinks the technological age is about.

01:44:00.000 --> 01:44:04.000
And he thinks that's different from every other age in history.

01:44:04.000 --> 01:44:09.000
We used to think of ourselves in the 17th century at the beginning of the Enlightenment

01:44:09.000 --> 01:44:14.000
as subjects who represent objects.

01:44:14.000 --> 01:44:20.000
Descartes thought that a subject is something, some mental sort of realm

01:44:20.000 --> 01:44:23.000
that represents the world in a certain way.

01:44:23.000 --> 01:44:30.000
And we are closed in on ourselves in the sense that we have a special relation to our representations.

01:44:30.000 --> 01:44:33.000
That's what the realm of the subject is.

01:44:33.000 --> 01:44:37.000
But others, in the Middle Ages, we were created in the image and likeness of God.

01:44:37.000 --> 01:44:44.000
And in the pre-Socratic age, to be was to be what wooshes up and lingers for a while

01:44:44.000 --> 01:44:49.000
and fades away the paradigm of what is where thunder storms

01:44:49.000 --> 01:44:54.000
and the anger of the gods, Achilles' battle fury.

01:44:54.000 --> 01:44:58.000
And it overtakes everything and stays for a while and then leaves.

01:44:58.000 --> 01:45:01.000
The flowers blooming in spring.

01:45:01.000 --> 01:45:05.000
And that's very different from the way we experience ourselves.

01:45:05.000 --> 01:45:09.000
So the question is, what are we supposed to do in the face of that?

01:45:09.000 --> 01:45:19.000
And Heidegger thinks that the presupposition that's motivated everything from the pre-Socratics forward

01:45:19.000 --> 01:45:29.000
is that there is some entity that's the ground of the way we understand everything to be.

01:45:29.000 --> 01:45:31.000
For the Middle Ages, it was God.

01:45:31.000 --> 01:45:35.000
That was the entity that made things be the things that they are.

01:45:35.000 --> 01:45:39.000
For the Enlightenment, it was us, maybe first art.

01:45:39.000 --> 01:45:40.000
It's us.

01:45:40.000 --> 01:45:47.000
And Heidegger thinks whatever it is that stands at the ground of what we are, it's not another thing.

01:45:47.000 --> 01:45:49.000
It's not another entity.

01:45:49.000 --> 01:45:53.000
And we're relating to it in the wrong way if we think of it like that.

01:45:53.000 --> 01:45:57.000
There's some way, and this is partly why I was interested in Meister Eckhart.

01:45:57.000 --> 01:46:02.000
He says, what there is, is there's giving going on in the world.

01:46:02.000 --> 01:46:07.000
And we're the grateful recipient of it.

01:46:07.000 --> 01:46:12.000
And the giving is like whatever it is, it's the social norms that we're thrown into.

01:46:12.000 --> 01:46:13.000
We didn't choose them.

01:46:13.000 --> 01:46:14.000
They were given to us.

01:46:14.000 --> 01:46:15.000
And that's the ground.

01:46:15.000 --> 01:46:19.000
That is what makes it possible for anything to be intelligible at all.

01:46:19.000 --> 01:46:25.000
If we lived outside of communities, if we lived in a world where there were no social norms at all,

01:46:25.000 --> 01:46:27.000
nothing would mean anything.

01:46:27.000 --> 01:46:29.000
Nothing would have any significance.

01:46:29.000 --> 01:46:35.000
Nothing would be regular in the way that things need to be regular in order for there to be departures

01:46:35.000 --> 01:46:38.000
or manifestations of that regularity.

01:46:38.000 --> 01:46:45.000
So community norms are crucial, but they're also always updating.

01:46:45.000 --> 01:46:53.000
We have some responsibility for what they are and the way in which they're updating themselves.

01:46:54.000 --> 01:46:57.000
And yet we didn't ever choose it to be that way.

01:46:57.000 --> 01:47:06.000
So those norms are somehow giving significance to us in a way that we're implicated in.

01:47:06.000 --> 01:47:08.000
We have some relation to.

01:47:08.000 --> 01:47:13.000
And all that gets covered over if you think of us as efficient resources to be optimized.

01:47:13.000 --> 01:47:19.000
Is that a conflicting view that we are resources to be optimized?

01:47:19.000 --> 01:47:24.000
Is that somehow deeply conflicting with the fact that there is a ground that we stand on?

01:47:24.000 --> 01:47:25.000
Absolutely.

01:47:25.000 --> 01:47:31.000
So what Heidegger thinks is that he calls this the supreme danger of the technological age,

01:47:31.000 --> 01:47:35.000
is that without ever having chosen it, without ever having decided it,

01:47:35.000 --> 01:47:38.000
this is the way we understand what it is to be us.

01:47:38.000 --> 01:47:46.000
But he thinks that it's also, he says, quoting Holderlin, this 18th century German poet,

01:47:46.000 --> 01:47:51.000
he says, in the supreme danger lies the saving possibility.

01:47:51.000 --> 01:47:53.000
So what does that mean?

01:47:53.000 --> 01:47:58.000
It means that this is the understanding that we've been thrown into, that we've been given.

01:47:58.000 --> 01:48:00.000
It's the gift that was given to us.

01:48:00.000 --> 01:48:02.000
It's supremely dangerous.

01:48:02.000 --> 01:48:06.000
If we let ourselves live that way, we'll destroy ourselves.

01:48:06.000 --> 01:48:14.000
But it's also the saving possibility because if we recognize that we never chose that,

01:48:14.000 --> 01:48:20.000
that it was given to us, but also we were implicated in its being given,

01:48:20.000 --> 01:48:26.000
and we could find a way to supersede it, that it's the ground, but it's also updatable.

01:48:26.000 --> 01:48:29.000
He calls the ground the groundless ground.

01:48:29.000 --> 01:48:38.000
It's not like an entity which is there, solid, stable, like God, who's eternal and non-changing.

01:48:38.000 --> 01:48:43.000
It's always updating itself, and we're always involved in its being updated.

01:48:43.000 --> 01:48:49.000
We're only involved in it in the right way if we listen, like Miles Davis.

01:48:49.000 --> 01:48:55.000
Optimization is not a good way to live life.

01:48:55.000 --> 01:49:02.000
If you thought that it was obviously clear that that was the relevant value,

01:49:02.000 --> 01:49:07.000
so obviously clear that it never even occurred to you to ask whether it was right to think that,

01:49:07.000 --> 01:49:09.000
then you would be in danger.

01:49:09.000 --> 01:49:10.000
Got it.

01:49:10.000 --> 01:49:16.000
There is some in this modern technological age in the full meaning of the word technology

01:49:16.000 --> 01:49:22.000
that's updated to actual modern age with a lot more technology going on.

01:49:22.000 --> 01:49:31.000
It does feel like colleagues of mine in the tech space actually are somehow drawn to that optimization,

01:49:31.000 --> 01:49:39.000
as if that's going to save us, as if the thing that truly weighs us down is the inefficiencies.

01:49:39.000 --> 01:49:40.000
Exactly.

01:49:40.000 --> 01:49:45.000
I think if you think about other contexts, what are the moments when ...

01:49:45.000 --> 01:49:47.000
We're unique in this respect.

01:49:47.000 --> 01:49:51.000
This period in history is unlike any previous period.

01:49:51.000 --> 01:49:53.000
Nobody ever felt that way.

01:49:53.000 --> 01:49:58.000
But think about, but it's also true that no previous period in history was nihilistic.

01:49:58.000 --> 01:50:00.000
Our condition is tied up.

01:50:00.000 --> 01:50:06.000
That sort of thing is meant to be a response to the felt lack of a ground.

01:50:07.000 --> 01:50:11.000
No previous epoch in history felt that way.

01:50:11.000 --> 01:50:13.000
They didn't have our problem.

01:50:15.000 --> 01:50:23.000
It was much more natural to them to experience moments in ways that feel unachievable for us,

01:50:23.000 --> 01:50:26.000
what we were calling moments of aliveness before.

01:50:26.000 --> 01:50:29.000
Think about the context in which they felt them.

01:50:29.000 --> 01:50:32.000
They weren't efficient, optimized contexts.

01:50:32.000 --> 01:50:34.000
Think about the Greeks.

01:50:34.000 --> 01:50:35.000
They never read Homer.

01:50:35.000 --> 01:50:37.000
It is a bizarre world back there.

01:50:37.000 --> 01:50:45.000
But one of the things that's bizarre is that they're so unmotivated by efficiency and optimizing

01:50:45.000 --> 01:50:52.000
that the only thing that seems to run through all of the different Greek cultures

01:50:52.000 --> 01:51:00.000
is the idea that if some stranger comes by, you better take care of them.

01:51:01.000 --> 01:51:05.000
Because Zeus is the God of strangers and Zeus will be angry.

01:51:05.000 --> 01:51:06.000
That's what they say.

01:51:06.000 --> 01:51:08.000
But how does it manifest itself?

01:51:08.000 --> 01:51:12.000
Odysseus, he's trying to get home and he gets shipwrecked on an island.

01:51:12.000 --> 01:51:17.000
And he's trying to figure out how he's been at sea for 10 days.

01:51:17.000 --> 01:51:18.000
He's starving.

01:51:18.000 --> 01:51:23.000
He's bedraggled and he sees now Cissa, the princess who's beautiful.

01:51:23.000 --> 01:51:28.000
And he's like, boy, I better get some clothes or something.

01:51:28.000 --> 01:51:31.000
I don't want them to beat me up and kill me.

01:51:31.000 --> 01:51:34.000
So she takes him to the palace.

01:51:34.000 --> 01:51:40.000
They have three days of banquets and festivals before they even ask his name.

01:51:40.000 --> 01:51:43.000
It's like, here's a stranger.

01:51:43.000 --> 01:51:49.000
Our job is to celebrate the presence of a stranger because this is where significance lies.

01:51:49.000 --> 01:51:51.000
Now, we don't have to feel that way.

01:51:51.000 --> 01:51:55.000
But the idea that that's one of the places where significance could lie

01:51:55.000 --> 01:52:01.000
is pretty strongly at odds with the idea that our salvation is going to come from optimization and efficiency.

01:52:01.000 --> 01:52:07.000
Now, maybe something about the way we live our lives will have that integrated into it.

01:52:07.000 --> 01:52:11.000
But it's at odds with other moments.

01:52:11.000 --> 01:52:16.000
Let me ask you a question about Hubert Dreyfus.

01:52:16.000 --> 01:52:23.000
He is a friend, a colleague, a mentor of yours, unfortunately no longer with us.

01:52:23.000 --> 01:52:28.000
You wrote with him the book titled All Things Shining,

01:52:28.000 --> 01:52:33.000
Reading the Western Classics to Find Meaning in a Secular Age.

01:52:33.000 --> 01:52:39.000
First, can you maybe speak about who that man was, what you learned from him?

01:52:39.000 --> 01:52:46.000
And then we could maybe ask how do we find through the classics, meaning in a secular age?

01:52:46.000 --> 01:52:48.000
Okay.

01:52:48.000 --> 01:52:58.000
So, Hubert Dreyfus was a very important philosopher of the late 20th, early 21st century.

01:52:58.000 --> 01:53:03.000
He died in 2017, about a little over four years ago.

01:53:03.000 --> 01:53:04.000
He was my teacher.

01:53:04.000 --> 01:53:09.000
I met him in 1989 when I went away to graduate school in Berkeley.

01:53:09.000 --> 01:53:10.000
That's where he taught.

01:53:10.000 --> 01:53:16.000
He plays an interesting and important role in the history of philosophy in America

01:53:16.000 --> 01:53:25.000
because in a period when most philosophers in America and in the English-speaking world

01:53:25.000 --> 01:53:30.000
were not taking seriously 20th century French and German philosophy, he was.

01:53:30.000 --> 01:53:37.000
And he was really probably the most important English-speaking interpreter of Heidegger,

01:53:37.000 --> 01:53:41.000
the German philosopher that we've been talking about.

01:53:41.000 --> 01:53:44.000
He was an incredible teacher.

01:53:44.000 --> 01:53:47.000
A lot of his influence came through his teaching.

01:53:47.000 --> 01:54:01.000
And one of the amazing things about him as a teacher was his sort of mix of intellectual humility

01:54:01.000 --> 01:54:05.000
with sort of deep, insightful authority.

01:54:05.000 --> 01:54:09.000
And he would stand up in front of a class of 300 students.

01:54:09.000 --> 01:54:13.000
You've taught huge classes because people love to go see him.

01:54:13.000 --> 01:54:20.000
And I taught for him for many years and say, you know, I've been reading this text for 40 years,

01:54:20.000 --> 01:54:23.000
but the question you asked is one I've never asked.

01:54:23.000 --> 01:54:25.000
And it would be true.

01:54:25.000 --> 01:54:32.000
He would find in what people said things that were surprising and new to him.

01:54:32.000 --> 01:54:33.000
And that's humility, actually.

01:54:33.000 --> 01:54:36.000
That is listening to the world.

01:54:36.000 --> 01:54:37.000
Absolutely.

01:54:37.000 --> 01:54:38.000
Absolutely.

01:54:38.000 --> 01:54:44.000
And he was always ready to be surprised by something that someone said.

01:54:44.000 --> 01:54:47.000
And there's something astonishing about that.

01:54:47.000 --> 01:54:53.000
So his influence was, you know, for people who didn't know him through his interpretations of these texts,

01:54:53.000 --> 01:54:55.000
he wrote about a huge range of stuff.

01:54:55.000 --> 01:54:58.000
But for people who didn't know him, it was through his presence.

01:54:58.000 --> 01:55:02.000
It was through the way he carried himself in his life.

01:55:02.000 --> 01:55:05.000
And so in any case, that's who he was.

01:55:05.000 --> 01:55:10.000
Because we, I graduated after many years as a graduate student.

01:55:10.000 --> 01:55:12.000
I didn't start in philosophy.

01:55:12.000 --> 01:55:14.000
I started in math, math and computer science, actually.

01:55:14.000 --> 01:55:18.000
And then I did a lot of work in computational neuroscience for a few years.

01:55:18.000 --> 01:55:20.000
It's a fascinating journey.

01:55:20.000 --> 01:55:24.000
We'll get to it through our friendly conversation about artificial intelligence.

01:55:24.000 --> 01:55:25.000
Okay.

01:55:25.000 --> 01:55:26.000
I'm sure.

01:55:26.000 --> 01:55:32.000
Because you're basically fascinated with the philosophy of mind, of the human mind,

01:55:32.000 --> 01:55:39.000
but rooted in a curiosity of mind through its artificial, through the engineering of mind.

01:55:39.000 --> 01:55:40.000
Yeah.

01:55:40.000 --> 01:55:41.000
Yeah, that's right.

01:55:41.000 --> 01:55:48.000
So Bert, I mean, the reason I was attracted to him actually is because of his, to begin with,

01:55:48.000 --> 01:55:54.000
was because of his criticisms of what was called traditional symbolic AI in the 70s and 80s.

01:55:54.000 --> 01:55:59.000
So I came to Berkeley as a graduate student who'd done a lot of math and a lot of computer science,

01:55:59.000 --> 01:56:01.000
a lot of computational neuroscience.

01:56:01.000 --> 01:56:07.000
I noticed that you had, you interview a lot of people in this world.

01:56:07.000 --> 01:56:14.000
And I had a teacher at Brown as an undergraduate, Jim Anderson, who wrote with Jeff Hinton,

01:56:14.000 --> 01:56:16.000
a big book on neural networks.

01:56:16.000 --> 01:56:19.000
So I had, I was interested in that.

01:56:19.000 --> 01:56:26.000
Not so interested in traditional AI, like sort of Lisp programings, things that went on in the 80s.

01:56:26.000 --> 01:56:31.000
Because it felt sort of, you know, when you made a system do something,

01:56:31.000 --> 01:56:34.000
all of a sudden it was an uninteresting thing to have done.

01:56:34.000 --> 01:56:39.000
The fact that you'd solved the problem that made it clear that the problem wasn't an interesting one to solve.

01:56:39.000 --> 01:56:40.000
That's right.

01:56:40.000 --> 01:56:42.000
And I had that experience.

01:56:42.000 --> 01:56:49.000
And Bert had criticisms of symbolic AI, what he called good old fashioned AI, GOFI.

01:56:49.000 --> 01:56:58.000
And I was attracted to those criticisms because it felt to me that there was something lacking in that project.

01:56:58.000 --> 01:57:00.000
And I didn't know what it was.

01:57:00.000 --> 01:57:02.000
I just felt its absence.

01:57:02.000 --> 01:57:12.000
And then I learned that all his arguments came from his reading of this phenomenological and existential tradition.

01:57:12.000 --> 01:57:15.000
And so I had to try to figure out what those folks were saying.

01:57:15.000 --> 01:57:17.000
And it was a long road, let me tell you.

01:57:18.000 --> 01:57:19.000
It took me a long time.

01:57:19.000 --> 01:57:21.000
But it was because of Bert that I was able to do that.

01:57:21.000 --> 01:57:24.000
So I owe him that huge debt of gratitude.

01:57:24.000 --> 01:57:28.000
And eventually we went on to write a book together, which was a great experience.

01:57:28.000 --> 01:57:31.000
And yes, we published All Things Shining in 2011.

01:57:31.000 --> 01:57:38.000
And that's a book that I definitely would not have had the chutzpah to try to write if it weren't for Bert.

01:57:38.000 --> 01:57:47.000
Because it was really about great literature in the history of the West from Homer and Virgil and Dante to Melville.

01:57:47.000 --> 01:57:54.000
There's a huge chapter on Melville, a big chapter on David Foster Wallace, who Bert didn't care about at all.

01:57:54.000 --> 01:57:56.000
But I was fascinated by it.

01:57:56.000 --> 01:58:04.000
And so learning to think that way while writing that book with him was an amazing experience.

01:58:04.000 --> 01:58:15.000
So I have to admit, one of my failings in life, one of many failings is I've never gotten through Moby Dick or any of Melville's works.

01:58:15.000 --> 01:58:28.000
So maybe can you comment on, before we talk about David Foster Wallace, who I have gotten through, what are some of the sources of meaning in these classics?

01:58:28.000 --> 01:58:29.000
Good.

01:58:29.000 --> 01:58:33.000
So Moby Dick, I think, is the other great novel of the 19th century.

01:58:33.000 --> 01:58:40.000
So the Brothers Karamazov and Moby Dick and they're diametrically opposed, which is one of the really interesting things.

01:58:40.000 --> 01:58:48.000
So the Brothers Karamazov is a kind of existential interpretation of Russian Orthodox Christianity.

01:58:48.000 --> 01:58:51.000
How do you live that way and find joy in your existence?

01:58:51.000 --> 01:58:55.000
Moby Dick is not at all about Christianity.

01:58:55.000 --> 01:59:08.000
It sort of starts with the observation that the form of Christianity that Ishmael is familiar with is broken.

01:59:08.000 --> 01:59:11.000
It's not going to work in his living, his life.

01:59:11.000 --> 01:59:12.000
He has to leave it.

01:59:12.000 --> 01:59:17.000
He has to go to sea in order to find what needs to happen.

01:59:17.000 --> 01:59:23.000
And Ishmael is the wailing boat captain?

01:59:23.000 --> 01:59:24.000
So he's not the captain.

01:59:24.000 --> 01:59:25.000
That's Ahab.

01:59:25.000 --> 01:59:26.000
Ahab is the captain.

01:59:26.000 --> 01:59:27.000
Yeah, right.

01:59:27.000 --> 01:59:28.000
Let me back up.

01:59:28.000 --> 01:59:31.000
The famous opening line to the book is, call me Ishmael.

01:59:31.000 --> 01:59:35.000
And Ishmael is the main character in the book.

01:59:35.000 --> 01:59:36.000
He's a nobody.

01:59:36.000 --> 01:59:37.000
He's you and me.

01:59:37.000 --> 01:59:39.000
He's the everyday guy.

01:59:39.000 --> 01:59:41.000
He's like a nobody on the ship.

01:59:41.000 --> 01:59:44.000
He's not the lowest, but certainly not the highest.

01:59:44.000 --> 01:59:46.000
He's right in the middle.

01:59:47.000 --> 01:59:55.000
And he's named Ishmael, which is interesting because Ishmael is the illegitimate son of Abraham in the Old Testament.

01:59:55.000 --> 02:00:01.000
He is the, I think if I have it right, again, someone will correct me.

02:00:01.000 --> 02:00:08.000
I think he's the one that Islam traces its genesis to.

02:00:08.000 --> 02:00:14.000
And so Islam is an Abrahamic religion, like Judaism and Christianity.

02:00:14.000 --> 02:00:21.000
But Judaism and Christianity trace their lineage through Isaac, the quote unquote legitimate son of Abraham.

02:00:21.000 --> 02:00:27.000
And Ishmael is the other son of Abraham, who he had with a girlfriend.

02:00:27.000 --> 02:00:32.000
And so he's clearly outside of Christianity in some way.

02:00:32.000 --> 02:00:38.000
He's named after the non-Christian sort of son of Abraham.

02:00:38.000 --> 02:00:44.000
And the book starts out with this, what does he call it?

02:00:44.000 --> 02:00:49.000
Something like a dark and misty November mood.

02:00:49.000 --> 02:00:56.000
He's walking along the street and he's overcome by his, I can't remember what the word is, but his hypos.

02:00:56.000 --> 02:00:57.000
That's what he calls them.

02:00:57.000 --> 02:00:59.000
He's in a mood.

02:00:59.000 --> 02:01:00.000
He's depressed.

02:01:00.000 --> 02:01:01.000
He's down.

02:01:01.000 --> 02:01:02.000
Things are not going well.

02:01:02.000 --> 02:01:04.000
And that's where he starts.

02:01:04.000 --> 02:01:18.000
And he signs up to go on this whaling voyage with this captain, Ahab, who is this incredibly charismatic, deeply disturbing character,

02:01:18.000 --> 02:01:25.000
who is a captain who's got lots of history and wants to go whaling, wants to get whales.

02:01:25.000 --> 02:01:26.000
That's what they do.

02:01:26.000 --> 02:01:31.000
They harpoon these whales and bring them back and sell the blubber and the oil and so on.

02:01:31.000 --> 02:01:35.000
So he's kind of rich and he's famous and he's powerful.

02:01:35.000 --> 02:01:37.000
He's an authority figure.

02:01:37.000 --> 02:01:44.000
And he is megalomaniacally obsessed with getting one particular whale, which is called Moby Dick.

02:01:44.000 --> 02:01:50.000
And Moby Dick is like the largest, the whitest, the sort of most terrifying of all the whales.

02:01:51.000 --> 02:02:00.000
And Ahab wants to get him because a number of years earlier, he had an encounter with Moby Dick where Moby Dick bit off his leg.

02:02:00.000 --> 02:02:08.000
And he survived, but he had this deeply religious experience in the wake of it.

02:02:08.000 --> 02:02:11.000
And he needed to find out what the meaning of that was.

02:02:11.000 --> 02:02:14.000
Like, what is the meaning of my suffering?

02:02:14.000 --> 02:02:22.000
Who am I such that the world and Moby Dick, this Leviathan at the center of it, should treat me this way?

02:02:22.000 --> 02:02:30.000
And so his task is not just to go whaling, it's to figure out the meaning of the universe through going whaling

02:02:30.000 --> 02:02:36.000
and having a confrontation with his tormentor, this whale, Moby Dick.

02:02:36.000 --> 02:02:44.000
And the confrontation is so weird because Melville points out that whales, their faces are so huge.

02:02:44.000 --> 02:02:46.000
Their foreheads are so huge.

02:02:46.000 --> 02:02:52.000
And their eyes are on the side of them that you can never actually look them in the eye.

02:02:52.000 --> 02:02:57.000
And it's kind of a metaphor for God, like you can't ever look God in the face.

02:02:57.000 --> 02:03:00.000
That's the sort of traditional thing to say about God.

02:03:00.000 --> 02:03:05.000
You can't find the ultimate meaning of the universe by looking God in the face.

02:03:05.000 --> 02:03:07.000
But Ahab wants to.

02:03:07.000 --> 02:03:11.000
He says he's got a paste-bored mask of a face.

02:03:11.000 --> 02:03:15.000
But I'll strike through the mask and find out what's behind.

02:03:15.000 --> 02:03:22.000
And so Ishmael is sort of caught up in this thing and he's like going whaling because he's in a bad mood.

02:03:22.000 --> 02:03:24.000
And maybe this will make things better.

02:03:24.000 --> 02:03:28.000
And he makes friends with this guy Quiquewag.

02:03:28.000 --> 02:03:30.000
And Quiquewag is a pagan.

02:03:30.000 --> 02:03:33.000
He's from an island in the South Pacific.

02:03:33.000 --> 02:03:38.000
And he's got tattoos all over his body, head to toe.

02:03:38.000 --> 02:03:45.000
He's party-colored, like every different color, says Ishmael, is these tattoos.

02:03:45.000 --> 02:03:58.000
And they are the writing on his body, he says, of the immutable mysteries of the universe as understood through his culture.

02:03:58.000 --> 02:04:06.000
And so somehow Quiquewag is this character who is like not Christian at all.

02:04:06.000 --> 02:04:09.000
And he's powerful in a very different way than Ahab is.

02:04:09.000 --> 02:04:11.000
He's supposed to be the king.

02:04:11.000 --> 02:04:14.000
He's the son of the king and probably his father's died by now.

02:04:14.000 --> 02:04:16.000
And if he went home, he'd be the king.

02:04:16.000 --> 02:04:21.000
But he's off on a voyage too, trying to understand who he is before he goes back and leads his people.

02:04:21.000 --> 02:04:25.000
And he's a harpooner, the bravest of the people on the ship.

02:04:25.000 --> 02:04:32.000
And he's got the mystery of the universe tattooed on his body, but nobody can understand it.

02:04:32.000 --> 02:04:41.000
And it's through his relation with Quiquewag that Ishmael comes to get a different understanding of what we might be about.

02:04:41.000 --> 02:04:44.000
So that's Moby Dick in a nutshell.

02:04:44.000 --> 02:04:49.000
And connected to a book I have read, which is funny.

02:04:49.000 --> 02:04:56.000
There's probably echoes that represent the 20th century now in Old Man and the Sea by Hemingway.

02:04:56.000 --> 02:05:07.000
That also has similar, I guess, themes, but more personal, more focused on the...

02:05:07.000 --> 02:05:09.000
I mean, I guess it's less about God.

02:05:09.000 --> 02:05:14.000
It's almost more like the existentialist version of Moby Dick and hence shorter.

02:05:14.000 --> 02:05:15.000
A lot shorter.

02:05:15.000 --> 02:05:18.000
Yeah, well, Hemingway was brilliant that way.

02:05:18.000 --> 02:05:23.000
But do you see echoes and do you find Old Man and the Sea interesting?

02:05:23.000 --> 02:05:29.000
It's been since ninth grade that I've been Old Man and the Sea even longer ago than the Fountainhead.

02:05:29.000 --> 02:05:31.000
So I didn't know we were going to go there.

02:05:31.000 --> 02:05:33.000
I mean, I find Hemingway interesting.

02:05:33.000 --> 02:05:44.000
But Hemingway, my general sort of picture of him is that we have to confront the dangers and the difficulties of our life.

02:05:44.000 --> 02:05:48.000
We have to develop in ourselves a certain kind of courage and manliness.

02:05:48.000 --> 02:05:50.000
And I think there's something interesting about that.

02:05:50.000 --> 02:05:53.000
He's for risk in a certain way.

02:05:53.000 --> 02:05:55.000
And I think that's important.

02:05:55.000 --> 02:06:02.000
But now I don't have any right to say this since it's been so long since I read it.

02:06:02.000 --> 02:06:05.000
I do feel like there's...

02:06:05.000 --> 02:06:11.000
I don't remember a sense for quite the tragedy of it.

02:06:11.000 --> 02:06:12.000
Maybe there is.

02:06:12.000 --> 02:06:14.000
Is it a melancholy novel?

02:06:14.000 --> 02:06:15.000
I don't even remember.

02:06:15.000 --> 02:06:20.000
No, it has a sense like The Stranger by Camus.

02:06:20.000 --> 02:06:24.000
It has a sense of this is how life is.

02:06:24.000 --> 02:06:36.000
And it has more about old age and that you're not quite the man you used to be feeling of this is how time passes.

02:06:36.000 --> 02:06:43.000
And then the passing of time and how you get older and this is one last fish.

02:06:43.000 --> 02:06:46.000
It's less about this is the fish.

02:06:46.000 --> 02:06:49.000
It's more like this is one last fish.

02:06:49.000 --> 02:06:56.000
And asking who was I as a man as a human being in this world?

02:06:56.000 --> 02:07:00.000
And this one fish helps you ask that question fully.

02:07:00.000 --> 02:07:01.000
Wonderful.

02:07:01.000 --> 02:07:06.000
But it's one fish, which is just sort of all the other fish too.

02:07:06.000 --> 02:07:13.000
And that is a big difference because for Ahab, no other fish will do than Moby Dick.

02:07:13.000 --> 02:07:18.000
It's got to be the biggest, the most powerful, the most tormenting.

02:07:18.000 --> 02:07:22.000
It's got to be the one that you've got history with that has defiled you.

02:07:22.000 --> 02:07:27.000
And it's a raucous ride, Moby Dick.

02:07:28.000 --> 02:07:30.000
What about David Foster Wallace?

02:07:30.000 --> 02:07:36.000
So why is he important to you in the search of meaning in a secular age?

02:07:36.000 --> 02:07:37.000
Good.

02:07:37.000 --> 02:07:40.000
So I'll just just to finish the Moby Dick thing.

02:07:40.000 --> 02:07:48.000
I think what's interesting about Melville is that he thinks our salvation comes not if we get in the right relation to monotheism or Christianity,

02:07:48.000 --> 02:07:54.000
but if we get in the right relation to polytheism to the idea that there's not a unity to our existence.

02:07:54.000 --> 02:07:58.000
But there are lots of little meanings and they don't cohere.

02:07:58.000 --> 02:08:05.000
Sometimes, you know, like in Homer, sometimes you're in love.

02:08:05.000 --> 02:08:09.000
Helen's in love with Paris and they do crazy things.

02:08:09.000 --> 02:08:12.000
They go off and run away and the Trojan War begins.

02:08:12.000 --> 02:08:14.000
And sometimes you're in a battle fury.

02:08:14.000 --> 02:08:20.000
Their love is Aphrodite's realm and the battle fury, that's Ares realm and that's a totally different world.

02:08:20.000 --> 02:08:22.000
And they're not even, I mean, they're related.

02:08:22.000 --> 02:08:25.000
There's a kind of family resemblance, but not much.

02:08:25.000 --> 02:08:30.000
Mostly you're just in different sort of local meaningful worlds.

02:08:30.000 --> 02:08:36.000
And Melville seems to think that that's a thing that we could aim to bring back.

02:08:36.000 --> 02:08:47.000
He says we have to lure back the Mary May Day gods of old and lovingly enthrone them in the now egotistical sky, the now unhaunted hill.

02:08:47.000 --> 02:08:52.000
That's what we live in this world where hills aren't haunted with significance anymore.

02:08:52.000 --> 02:08:58.000
And the sky is just a bunch of stuff that we're studying with physics and astrophysics and stuff.

02:08:58.000 --> 02:09:04.000
But they used to be awe-inspiring and we have to figure out how to get in that relation to them.

02:09:04.000 --> 02:09:11.000
But not by trying to give a unity to our existence through developing habits and practices that get written on our body.

02:09:12.000 --> 02:09:19.000
And so his is about the end of Judeo-Christianity and the sort of Roman appropriation of it.

02:09:19.000 --> 02:09:29.000
In Wallace, one of the things I think is so interesting about him is that I think he is a great observer of the contemporary world.

02:09:29.000 --> 02:09:31.000
And he's a very funny writer.

02:09:31.000 --> 02:09:35.000
I mean, he's really funny, but he's a great observer of the contemporary world.

02:09:35.000 --> 02:09:44.000
And what he thought was at the core of the contemporary world was this constant temptation to diversion through entertainment.

02:09:44.000 --> 02:09:49.000
That's a different story than Heidegger's story about efficiency and optimization.

02:09:49.000 --> 02:09:51.000
But it's the other side of it.

02:09:51.000 --> 02:09:55.000
Like, what is this temptation sort of diverting us from?

02:09:55.000 --> 02:09:58.000
The ability to be more efficient.

02:09:58.000 --> 02:10:08.000
So, you know, you're tempted to go watch some stupid film or television show or something that's dumb and not really very interesting.

02:10:08.000 --> 02:10:15.000
But you read that temptation as a temptation precisely in virtue of it's taking you away from your optimizing your existence.

02:10:15.000 --> 02:10:18.000
And so I think there are two sides of the same coin.

02:10:18.000 --> 02:10:20.000
I think he's brilliant at describing it.

02:10:20.000 --> 02:10:27.000
I think he thought it was a desperate position to be in that it was something that we needed to confront.

02:10:27.000 --> 02:10:29.000
And find a way out of.

02:10:29.000 --> 02:10:32.000
And his characters are trying to do that.

02:10:32.000 --> 02:10:36.000
And I think there's two different David Foster Wallace's.

02:10:36.000 --> 02:10:40.000
One, I mean, David Foster Wallace committed suicide.

02:10:40.000 --> 02:10:42.000
And when I, and it's very sad.

02:10:42.000 --> 02:10:49.000
And he clearly did have, you know, sort of, there was a physiological basis to his condition.

02:10:49.000 --> 02:10:50.000
He knew it.

02:10:50.000 --> 02:10:53.000
He was treating it for decades with medication.

02:10:53.000 --> 02:10:56.000
He had electroshock therapy a number of times.

02:10:56.000 --> 02:10:59.000
It's just very, very sad story.

02:10:59.000 --> 02:11:03.000
When I decided that we were going to write about David Foster Wallace.

02:11:03.000 --> 02:11:16.000
The first thing I was worried about is what can you, can you like obviously a motivating factor, maybe the motivating factor in his committing suicide was his physiological condition.

02:11:16.000 --> 02:11:20.000
But there was, there's, there's this, there was a question.

02:11:21.000 --> 02:11:31.000
Could you think, I mean, he's obsessed with the condition, with what we need to do to achieve our salvation, to live well, to make our lives worth living.

02:11:31.000 --> 02:11:37.000
And he clearly in the end felt like he couldn't do that.

02:11:37.000 --> 02:11:49.000
So in addition to the physiological thing, which probably most of it, the question for me was, could you find in his writing what his, what he was identifying as the thing we needed to do?

02:11:51.000 --> 02:11:54.000
That he nevertheless felt we couldn't be doing.

02:11:54.000 --> 02:11:59.000
And he, and he talks as if that's, that's the difficulty for him.

02:11:59.000 --> 02:12:01.000
So, so that, that's one side of him.

02:12:01.000 --> 02:12:03.000
And I did want to find that.

02:12:03.000 --> 02:12:07.000
I think there's another side of him that's very different, but you were going to ask.

02:12:07.000 --> 02:12:08.000
No, please.

02:12:08.000 --> 02:12:09.000
What's the other side?

02:12:09.000 --> 02:12:20.000
I mean, what I write about in the, in the chapter mostly is what I think he's got as our, as, as our saving possibility.

02:12:20.000 --> 02:12:33.000
He thinks our saving possibility, he says this in a graduation speech that he gave to Kenyon, is that we have the freedom to interpret situations however we like.

02:12:33.000 --> 02:12:36.000
So what's the problem case for him?

02:12:36.000 --> 02:12:40.000
He says, look, you know, the problem case, we have, we have it all the time.

02:12:40.000 --> 02:12:42.000
You get pissed off at the world.

02:12:42.000 --> 02:12:56.000
You know, some, some big SUV cuts you off on the highway and you're pissed off and you might express your anger with one finger or another directed at that person.

02:12:56.000 --> 02:13:04.000
And he says, but actually, you know, you're being pissed off as the result of your having made an assumption.

02:13:04.000 --> 02:13:08.000
And the assumption is that that action was directed at you.

02:13:08.000 --> 02:13:14.000
Like the assumption is that you're the center of the universe and you shouldn't assume that.

02:13:14.000 --> 02:13:24.000
And the way to talk yourself out of it, he says, is to recognize the possibility that maybe that wasn't an action directed at you.

02:13:24.000 --> 02:13:36.000
Like maybe that guy is racing to the hospital, you know, to take care of his dying spouse who's been there suffering, you know, from cancer.

02:13:36.000 --> 02:13:44.000
Or maybe he's, you know, on the way to pick up a sick child or maybe he's, and it's not an action directed.

02:13:44.000 --> 02:13:48.000
That was your assumption, not something that was inherent in the situation.

02:13:48.000 --> 02:13:51.000
And I think there's something interesting about that.

02:13:51.000 --> 02:13:54.000
I think there's something right about that.

02:13:54.000 --> 02:14:06.000
At the same time, I don't think he speaks as if we can just spin out these stories and whether they're true or not doesn't matter.

02:14:06.000 --> 02:14:10.000
What matters is that they free us from this assumption.

02:14:10.000 --> 02:14:11.000
Yes.

02:14:11.000 --> 02:14:15.000
And I think they only free us from this assumption if they're true.

02:14:15.000 --> 02:14:20.000
Like sometimes the guy really did direct it at you and that's part of the situation.

02:14:20.000 --> 02:14:23.000
And like you can't pretend that it's not part of the situation.

02:14:23.000 --> 02:14:25.000
You have to find the right way of dealing with that situation.

02:14:25.000 --> 02:14:32.000
So you have to listen to what's actually happening and then you have to figure out how to make it right.

02:14:32.000 --> 02:14:35.000
And I think he thinks that we have too much freedom.

02:14:35.000 --> 02:14:37.000
He thinks that you don't have to listen to the situation.

02:14:37.000 --> 02:14:40.000
You can just tell whatever story you like about it.

02:14:40.000 --> 02:14:43.000
And I think that's actually too tough.

02:14:43.000 --> 02:14:46.000
I don't think we have that kind of freedom.

02:14:46.000 --> 02:14:58.000
And he writes these incredibly moving letters when he's trying to write The Pale King, which is the unfinished novel that really sort of drove him to distraction.

02:14:58.000 --> 02:15:11.000
At the center of the novel is this character who one of the characters at the center of the novel is a guy who's doing the most boring thing you could possibly imagine.

02:15:11.000 --> 02:15:14.000
He is an IRS tax examiner.

02:15:14.000 --> 02:15:21.000
He's going over other people's tax returns trying to figure out whether they follow the rules or not.

02:15:21.000 --> 02:15:27.000
And like just the idea of doing that for eight hours a day is just terrifying.

02:15:27.000 --> 02:15:40.000
And he puts this guy in an enormous warehouse that extends for miles where person after person after person is in rows of desks sort of nameless.

02:15:40.000 --> 02:15:42.000
Each of them doing this task.

02:15:42.000 --> 02:15:48.000
So he's in nowhere doing nothing and it's got to be intensely boring.

02:15:48.000 --> 02:15:53.000
And now the main character is trying to teach himself to do that.

02:15:53.000 --> 02:15:56.000
And the question is how do you put up with the boredom?

02:15:56.000 --> 02:16:00.000
How do you put up with this onslaught of meaninglessness?

02:16:00.000 --> 02:16:17.000
And the main character is able to confront that condition with such bliss that he literally levitates from happiness while he's going over other people's tax returns.

02:16:17.000 --> 02:16:23.000
And that's my metaphor for what I think Wallace must have imagined we have to try to aspire to.

02:16:24.000 --> 02:16:26.000
And I think that's unlivable.

02:16:26.000 --> 02:16:29.000
I think that's not an ambition that we could achieve.

02:16:29.000 --> 02:16:31.000
I think there's something else we could achieve.

02:16:31.000 --> 02:16:50.000
And the other thing that we can achieve that I think is something that he also is onto but doesn't write about as often is something more like achieving peak moments of significance in a situation when something great happens.

02:16:50.000 --> 02:16:54.000
And he writes about this in an article about Roger Federer.

02:16:54.000 --> 02:16:55.000
He loved tennis.

02:16:55.000 --> 02:16:57.000
Are you a tennis lover?

02:16:57.000 --> 02:17:01.000
I'm not a lover of tennis, but I played tennis for 15 years and so on.

02:17:01.000 --> 02:17:05.000
I don't love it the way people love baseball, for example.

02:17:05.000 --> 02:17:07.000
I see the beauty in it, the artistry.

02:17:07.000 --> 02:17:09.000
I just like that as a sport.

02:17:09.000 --> 02:17:10.000
Good.

02:17:10.000 --> 02:17:11.000
Okay.

02:17:11.000 --> 02:17:14.000
Well, I didn't play much tennis, but I hit a ball around every once in a while as a kid.

02:17:14.000 --> 02:17:16.000
And I always thought it was boring to watch.

02:17:17.000 --> 02:17:23.000
But reading David Foster Wallace on Roger Federer, you're like, wow, I've been missing something.

02:17:23.000 --> 02:17:28.000
And the article which appeared in the New York Times magazine was called Roger Federer as religious experience.

02:17:28.000 --> 02:17:29.000
Oh, wow.

02:17:29.000 --> 02:17:30.000
There you go.

02:17:30.000 --> 02:17:40.000
And he says, look, there's something astonishing about watching someone who's got a body like us and having a body is a limitation.

02:17:40.000 --> 02:17:46.000
It's like the sight of sores and pains and agony and exhaustion.

02:17:46.000 --> 02:17:50.000
And it's the thing that dies in the end.

02:17:50.000 --> 02:17:53.000
And so it's what we have to confront.

02:17:53.000 --> 02:17:56.000
I mean, there's also joys that go along with having a body.

02:17:56.000 --> 02:17:58.000
Like if you didn't have a body, there'd be no sex.

02:17:58.000 --> 02:18:03.000
If you didn't have a body, there'd be no sort of physical excitement and so on.

02:18:03.000 --> 02:18:08.000
But somehow having a body is essentially a limitation.

02:18:09.000 --> 02:18:20.000
That when you watch someone who's got one and is extraordinary at the way they use it, you can recognize how that limitation can be to some degree transcended.

02:18:20.000 --> 02:18:30.000
And that that's what we can get when we watch Federer or some other great athlete sort of doing these things that transcend the limitations of their bodies.

02:18:31.000 --> 02:18:38.000
And that that's the kind of peak experience that we're capable of that could be a kind of salvation.

02:18:38.000 --> 02:18:40.000
That's a very different story.

02:18:40.000 --> 02:18:42.000
And I think that's a livable story.

02:18:42.000 --> 02:18:51.000
And I don't know if it would have saved him, but I feel like I wish he'd developed that side of the story more.

02:18:51.000 --> 02:18:59.000
Can we talk about, and first of all, let me just comment that I deeply appreciate that you said you were going to say something.

02:18:59.000 --> 02:19:03.000
The fact that you're listening to me is amazing, like that you care about other humans.

02:19:03.000 --> 02:19:05.000
I really appreciate that.

02:19:05.000 --> 02:19:08.000
We should be in this way listening to the world.

02:19:08.000 --> 02:19:14.000
So that's a meta comment about many of the things we're talking about.

02:19:14.000 --> 02:19:26.000
But you mentioned something about levitating and a task that is infinitely boring and contrasting that with essentially levitating on a task that is great.

02:19:26.000 --> 02:19:33.000
Like the highest achievement of this physical limiting body in playing tennis.

02:19:33.000 --> 02:19:35.000
Now, I often say this.

02:19:35.000 --> 02:19:42.000
I don't know where I heard David Foster Wallace say this, but he said that the key to life is to be unboreable.

02:19:42.000 --> 02:19:45.000
That is the embodiment of this philosophy.

02:19:45.000 --> 02:19:52.000
And when people ask me for advice, like young students, you know, I don't find this interesting.

02:19:52.000 --> 02:19:53.000
I don't find this interesting.

02:19:53.000 --> 02:19:55.000
How do I find the thing I'm passionate for?

02:19:55.000 --> 02:20:04.000
This would be very interesting to explore because you kind of say that that may not be a realizable thing to do, which is to be unboreable.

02:20:04.000 --> 02:20:07.000
But my advice usually is life is amazing.

02:20:07.000 --> 02:20:17.000
Like you should be able to, you should strive to discover the joy, the levitation in everything.

02:20:17.000 --> 02:20:23.000
And the thing you get stuck on for a longer period of time, that might be the thing you should stick to.

02:20:23.000 --> 02:20:26.000
But everything should be full of joy.

02:20:26.000 --> 02:20:38.000
So that kind of cynicism of saying life is boring is a thing that will prevent you from discovering the thing that will give you deep meaning and joy.

02:20:38.000 --> 02:20:45.000
But you're saying being unboreable is not actionable for a human being.

02:20:45.000 --> 02:20:48.000
So, okay, excellent question, deep question.

02:20:48.000 --> 02:21:01.000
And you might think because of the title of the book that Bert and I wrote, All Things Shining, that I think all things are shining.

02:21:01.000 --> 02:21:07.000
But actually, I think it's an unachievable goal to be unboreable.

02:21:07.000 --> 02:21:14.000
I do believe that you're right that a lot of times when people are bored with something,

02:21:14.000 --> 02:21:16.000
it's because they haven't tried hard enough.

02:21:16.000 --> 02:21:27.000
And I do think quite a lot of what makes people bored with something is that they haven't paid attention well enough and that they haven't listened, as you were saying.

02:21:27.000 --> 02:21:30.000
So I do think there's something to that.

02:21:30.000 --> 02:21:32.000
I think that's a deep insight.

02:21:32.000 --> 02:21:42.000
On the other hand, the perfection of that insight is that nothing is ever anything less than joyful.

02:21:42.000 --> 02:21:59.000
And I actually think that Dostoyevsky and Melville both agree, but in very different ways, that life involves a wide range of moods and that all of them are important.

02:21:59.000 --> 02:22:01.000
It involves grief.

02:22:01.000 --> 02:22:05.000
Like, I think when someone dies, it's appropriate to grieve.

02:22:05.000 --> 02:22:09.000
And it's not in the first instance joyful.

02:22:09.000 --> 02:22:17.000
It's related to joy because it makes the joys you feel when you feel them more intense.

02:22:17.000 --> 02:22:23.000
But it makes them more intense by putting you in the position of experiencing the opposite.

02:22:23.000 --> 02:22:36.000
And it's only because we're capable of a wide range of passionate responses to situations that I think the significances can be as meaningful as they are.

02:22:36.000 --> 02:22:40.000
So Melville, again, has this sort of interest.

02:22:40.000 --> 02:22:45.000
I mean, let's just say the guilt and the grief in the Brothers Karamazov.

02:22:45.000 --> 02:22:48.000
Alyosha loses his mentor, Father Zosima.

02:22:48.000 --> 02:22:50.000
He's grieving.

02:22:50.000 --> 02:22:52.000
It's super important that he's grieving.

02:22:52.000 --> 02:23:04.000
He has a religious conversion on the basis of grieving where he sees the sort of deep sort of beauty of everything that is, but it comes through the grief, not by avoiding the grief.

02:23:04.000 --> 02:23:11.000
And Melville says something like, Ishmael says something like, he says, I'm like a Catskill Mountain Eagle.

02:23:11.000 --> 02:23:13.000
The Catskills Mountains nearby.

02:23:13.000 --> 02:23:20.000
He says who's sort of flying high above the earth, going over the peaks and down into the valleys.

02:23:20.000 --> 02:23:26.000
I have these ups and these downs, but they're all invested with a kind of significance.

02:23:26.000 --> 02:23:32.000
They all happen at an enormously high height because it's through the mountains that I'm flying.

02:23:32.000 --> 02:23:37.000
And even when I'm down, it's a way of being up, but it's really down.

02:23:37.000 --> 02:23:41.000
It's just that it's a way of being up because it makes the ups even upper.

02:23:41.000 --> 02:23:47.000
Well, I guess then the perfectionism of that can be destructive.

02:23:47.000 --> 02:24:01.000
I mean, I tend to see, for example, grief, a loss of love as part of love in that it's a celebration of the richness of feelings you had when you had the love.

02:24:01.000 --> 02:24:11.000
So it's all part of the same experience, but if you turn it into an optimization problem where everything can be unboreable, then that can in itself be destructive.

02:24:11.000 --> 02:24:12.000
Yeah.

02:24:12.000 --> 02:24:13.000
Yeah.

02:24:13.000 --> 02:24:24.000
I heard this interview with David Foster Wallace on the internet where it's a video of him and there is like a foreign sounding reporter asking him questions.

02:24:24.000 --> 02:24:28.000
I think there's an accident of some sort, German, I think, something like that.

02:24:28.000 --> 02:24:32.000
And I don't know, it just painted a picture of such a human person.

02:24:32.000 --> 02:24:34.000
