So she kind of walked in doing the usual journalistic things of just kind of generic questions and just kind of asking very basic questions, but he brought out something in her over time.

02:24:53.000 --> 02:25:02.000
And he was so sensitive and so sensitive to her and also sensitive to being thinking and acting human in this world.

02:25:02.000 --> 02:25:06.000
That's just painted such a beautiful picture that people should go definitely check out.

02:25:06.000 --> 02:25:20.000
They made me really sad that we don't get this kind of picture of other thinkers, all of the ones we've been talking about, just that almost this little accidental view of this human being.

02:25:20.000 --> 02:25:21.000
I don't know.

02:25:21.000 --> 02:25:22.000
It was a beautiful one.

02:25:22.000 --> 02:25:25.000
And I guess there's not many like that, even of him.

02:25:25.000 --> 02:25:26.000
Yeah.

02:25:26.000 --> 02:25:27.000
Yeah.

02:25:27.000 --> 02:25:34.000
No, I think he was more than his writing ability, which was extraordinary.

02:25:34.000 --> 02:25:38.000
He had developed a style that was, I think, unlike anyone else's style.

02:25:38.000 --> 02:25:50.000
It was his sensitivity to other people and to sort of what he was there to pay attention to.

02:25:50.000 --> 02:25:58.000
He wants, in one of his essays, I think it's the one called an incredibly fun thing I'll never do again.

02:25:58.000 --> 02:26:00.000
I do know that one about cruise ships.

02:26:00.000 --> 02:26:10.000
I think he describes himself as this sort of roving eyeball that just sort of walks around the ship noticing things.

02:26:10.000 --> 02:26:13.000
And he was incredibly good at that.

02:26:13.000 --> 02:26:21.000
But I also worry that that reflects something that you find in Ivan, in the Brothers Karamazov.

02:26:21.000 --> 02:26:35.000
Ivan, I don't know if you remember this part, when he's away at school as a young, a college, as a young boy, he makes money by going around town to where tragic events have occurred.

02:26:35.000 --> 02:26:39.000
Someone just got run over by a carriage or someone, you know, something just happened.

02:26:39.000 --> 02:26:45.000
And being the first one there, he always knows somehow where these things are going to happen.

02:26:45.000 --> 02:26:52.000
And writing about it, giving this really good description and then signing it, I witness.

02:26:52.000 --> 02:27:02.000
And it's as if Ivan's understanding of his life is that he was supposed to be a witness to it.

02:27:02.000 --> 02:27:05.000
He was supposed to see others but not get involved.

02:27:05.000 --> 02:27:09.000
He never is interested in trying to keep the bad things from happening.

02:27:09.000 --> 02:27:12.000
He just wants to report on them when he sees them.

02:27:12.000 --> 02:27:17.000
And I think that he's an incredibly isolated person, character.

02:27:17.000 --> 02:27:34.000
And it's his isolation from others, from the love of others and his inability, his desire not to love others because that attaches him to someone that I think is really at the ground of his condition.

02:27:34.000 --> 02:27:39.000
And I think that aim to be isolated, which many people have nowadays.

02:27:39.000 --> 02:27:50.000
I mean, you see it in the underground man too, just sort of taking yourself out of the world because you don't want to have to take responsibility for being involved with others.

02:27:50.000 --> 02:27:52.000
I think that's a bad move.

02:27:52.000 --> 02:27:57.000
And I do worry that maybe, I mean, I never knew David Foster Wallace.

02:27:57.000 --> 02:28:01.000
I have no right to comment, you know, on his life.

02:28:01.000 --> 02:28:07.000
But he portrays himself in that one episode as a person who does that.

02:28:07.000 --> 02:28:09.000
And I think that's dangerous.

02:28:09.000 --> 02:28:12.000
Yeah, there's some sense in which being sensitive to the world.

02:28:12.000 --> 02:28:19.000
Like I find myself, the source of joy for me is just being really sensitive to the world, to experience.

02:28:19.000 --> 02:28:25.000
There's some way, it's quite brilliant where you're saying that that could be isolating.

02:28:25.000 --> 02:28:31.000
It's like Darwin studying a new kind of species on an island.

02:28:31.000 --> 02:28:33.000
You don't want to interfere with it.

02:28:33.000 --> 02:28:36.000
You find it so beautiful that you don't want to interfere with its beauty.

02:28:36.000 --> 02:28:49.000
So there is some sense in which that isolates you and then you find yourself deeply alone away from the experiences that bring you joy.

02:28:49.000 --> 02:28:51.000
And that could be destructive.

02:28:51.000 --> 02:28:55.000
That's fascinating how that works.

02:28:55.000 --> 02:29:01.000
And in his case, of course, some of it is just chemicals in his brain.

02:29:01.000 --> 02:29:09.000
But some of it is the path, his philosophy of life let him down.

02:29:09.000 --> 02:29:13.000
And that's the danger we need you to in gazing into the abyss.

02:29:13.000 --> 02:29:21.000
Your job is a difficult one because doing philosophy changes you.

02:29:21.000 --> 02:29:22.000
Yeah.

02:29:22.000 --> 02:29:29.000
And you may not know how it changes you until you're changed and you look in the mirror.

02:29:29.000 --> 02:29:38.000
You wrote a piece in MIT Tech Review saying that AI can't be an artist.

02:29:39.000 --> 02:29:44.000
Creativity is and always will be a human endeavor.

02:29:44.000 --> 02:29:48.000
You mentioned Burt and criticism of symbolic AI.

02:29:48.000 --> 02:29:59.000
Can you explain your view of criticizing the possible, the capacity for artistry and creativity in our robot friends?

02:29:59.000 --> 02:30:02.000
Yeah, I can try.

02:30:03.000 --> 02:30:17.000
So to make the argument, you have to have in mind what counts as art, what counts as a creative artistic act.

02:30:17.000 --> 02:30:23.000
I take it that just doing something new isn't sufficient.

02:30:23.000 --> 02:30:31.000
I mean, we say that good art is original, but not everything that's never been done before is good art.

02:30:31.000 --> 02:30:36.000
So there has to be more than just doing something new.

02:30:36.000 --> 02:30:48.000
It has to be somehow doing something new in a way that speaks to the audience or speaks to some portion of the audience at least.

02:30:48.000 --> 02:31:00.000
It has to be doing something new in such a way that some people who see or interact with it can see themselves anew in it.

02:31:00.000 --> 02:31:13.000
So I think that art is inherently a creative act, sorry, a kind of communicative act that it involves a relation with other people.

02:31:13.000 --> 02:31:18.000
So think about the conditions for that working.

02:31:18.000 --> 02:31:23.000
Someone, I talk in that article, I can't remember, something about new music.

02:31:23.000 --> 02:31:27.000
I think I don't talk about Stravinsky, but let's say Stravinsky.

02:31:28.000 --> 02:31:34.000
Stravinsky performs the Rite of Spring and there's riots.

02:31:34.000 --> 02:31:39.000
It is new and people hate it.

02:31:39.000 --> 02:31:42.000
It sounds like a cacophony.

02:31:42.000 --> 02:31:44.000
It sounds awful.

02:31:44.000 --> 02:31:50.000
It's written according to principles that are not like the principles of music composition that people are familiar with.

02:31:50.000 --> 02:31:54.000
So in some ways it's a failed communicative act.

02:31:54.000 --> 02:32:03.000
But as Nietzsche says about his own stuff, I mean, we now can recognize that it wasn't a failed communicative act.

02:32:03.000 --> 02:32:07.000
It just hadn't reached its time yet.

02:32:07.000 --> 02:32:15.000
And now that way of composing music is like, you know, it's in Disney movies.

02:32:15.000 --> 02:32:22.000
It's so part of our musical palette that we don't have that response.

02:32:22.000 --> 02:32:24.000
It changed us.

02:32:24.000 --> 02:32:27.000
It changed the way we understand what counts as good music.

02:32:27.000 --> 02:32:30.000
So that's a deep communicative act.

02:32:30.000 --> 02:32:36.000
It didn't perform its communication in that opening moment.

02:32:36.000 --> 02:32:42.000
But it did ultimately establish a new understanding for all of us of what counts as good art.

02:32:42.000 --> 02:32:47.000
And that's the kind of deep communication that I think good art can do.

02:32:47.000 --> 02:32:57.000
It can change our understanding of ourselves and of what a good manifestation of something of ourselves in a certain domain is.

02:32:57.000 --> 02:33:00.000
And use the term socially embedded.

02:33:00.000 --> 02:33:03.000
That art is fundamentally socially embedded.

02:33:03.000 --> 02:33:04.000
Yeah.

02:33:04.000 --> 02:33:16.000
And I really like that term because I see like my love for artificial intelligence and the kind of system that we can bring to the world that could make for an interesting

02:33:16.000 --> 02:33:24.000
and more lively world and one that enriches human beings is one where the AI systems are deeply socially embedded.

02:33:24.000 --> 02:33:25.000
Good.

02:33:25.000 --> 02:33:26.000
Yeah.

02:33:26.000 --> 02:33:32.000
So that and that actually is in contrast to the way artificial intelligence have been talked about throughout its history.

02:33:32.000 --> 02:33:41.000
And certainly now both on the robotics side and the AI side, it's especially on the tech sector where the businesses around AI,

02:33:41.000 --> 02:33:48.000
they kind of want to create systems that are like servants to humans.

02:33:48.000 --> 02:33:55.000
And then humans do all the beautiful human messiness of where art will be part.

02:33:55.000 --> 02:34:04.000
I think that there is no reason why you can't integrate AI systems in the way you integrate new humans to the picture.

02:34:04.000 --> 02:34:07.000
There are just the full diversity and the flaws.

02:34:07.000 --> 02:34:10.000
All of that adds to the thing.

02:34:11.000 --> 02:34:23.000
Now, you know, some people might say that AlphaZero is this system from DeepMind that was able to achieve, you know, solve the game,

02:34:23.000 --> 02:34:28.000
it beat the best people in the world that the game of go with no supervision from humans.

02:34:28.000 --> 02:34:36.000
But more interestingly to me on the side of creativity, it was able to surprise a lot of grandmasters with the kind of moves that came up with.

02:34:36.000 --> 02:34:43.000
Now, to me, that's not the creativity, the magic that's socially embedded that we're talking about.

02:34:43.000 --> 02:34:50.000
That is merely revealing the limitations of humans to discover.

02:34:50.000 --> 02:34:55.000
It's like to solve a particular aspect of a math problem.

02:34:56.000 --> 02:35:03.000
I think creativity is not just even socially embedded.

02:35:03.000 --> 02:35:07.000
It's the way you're saying it's part of the communicative act.

02:35:07.000 --> 02:35:11.000
It's the interactive, it's the dance with the culture.

02:35:11.000 --> 02:35:17.000
And so it has to be like for AlphaZero to be creative, truly creative,

02:35:17.000 --> 02:35:22.000
it would have to be integrated in a way where it has a Twitter account.

02:35:22.000 --> 02:35:30.000
And it becomes aware of the impact it has on the other grandmasters with the moves that's coming up.

02:35:30.000 --> 02:35:37.000
And there's one of the fascinating things about AlphaZero, which I just love so much,

02:35:37.000 --> 02:35:39.000
is I don't know if you're familiar with chess.

02:35:39.000 --> 02:35:40.000
I am, yeah.

02:35:40.000 --> 02:35:47.000
So it does certain things that most chess players, even at the highest level, don't do,

02:35:47.000 --> 02:35:55.000
which is it sacrifices pieces, it gives pieces away and then waits like 10 moves before it pays you back.

02:35:55.000 --> 02:35:58.000
So to me that's beautiful.

02:35:58.000 --> 02:36:03.000
That's art if only AlphaZero understood the artistry of that,

02:36:03.000 --> 02:36:09.000
which is I'm going to mess with you psychologically because I'm going to do two things.

02:36:09.000 --> 02:36:14.000
One, make you feel overconfident that you're doing well,

02:36:14.000 --> 02:36:19.000
but actually also once you realize you are playing AlphaZero that is much better than you,

02:36:19.000 --> 02:36:23.000
you're going to feel really nervous about what's on the way.

02:36:23.000 --> 02:36:25.000
This is the calm before the storm.

02:36:25.000 --> 02:36:30.000
And that creates a beautiful psychological masterpiece of this chess game.

02:36:30.000 --> 02:36:35.000
If only AlphaZero was then messing with you additionally to that

02:36:35.000 --> 02:36:39.000
and was cognizant of this doing that, then it becomes art.

02:36:39.000 --> 02:36:43.000
And then it's integrated into society in that way.

02:36:43.000 --> 02:36:52.000
And I believe it doesn't have to actually have an understanding of the world in the way that humans have.

02:36:52.000 --> 02:36:53.000
It can have a different one.

02:36:53.000 --> 02:36:59.000
It can be like a child is as clueless about so many aspects of the world and it's okay.

02:36:59.000 --> 02:37:02.000
And that's part of the magic of it, just being flawed,

02:37:02.000 --> 02:37:07.000
being lacking understanding all interesting kinds of ways, but interacting.

02:37:07.000 --> 02:37:10.000
So to me, it's possible to create art for AI,

02:37:10.000 --> 02:37:16.000
but exactly as you're saying in a deeply socially embedded way.

02:37:16.000 --> 02:37:17.000
Good.

02:37:17.000 --> 02:37:23.000
Well, I think we agree, but let me just highlight the thing that makes me think that we agree,

02:37:23.000 --> 02:37:36.000
which is that I think for people, for a community to allow themselves to recognize in a certain kind of creative act,

02:37:36.000 --> 02:37:40.000
I'm thinking of Stravinsky here, but we could think of a chess thing,

02:37:40.000 --> 02:37:50.000
to recognize in a certain kind of creative act a new and admirable, worthy way of thinking about what's significant in the situation.

02:37:50.000 --> 02:37:54.000
You have to believe that it wasn't random.

02:37:54.000 --> 02:38:04.000
You have to believe that Stravinsky wrote that way because he was receptive to what needed to be said now.

02:38:04.000 --> 02:38:16.000
And so you said if only AlphaZero could do all this by virtue of recognizing that this was the thing that needed to be done,

02:38:16.000 --> 02:38:19.000
then it would be socially embedded in the right way.

02:38:19.000 --> 02:38:21.000
And I think I agree with that.

02:38:21.000 --> 02:38:28.000
First of all, it's possible to do in a constrained domain, a game-playing domain, go or chess.

02:38:28.000 --> 02:38:32.000
Go is more complicated than chess, but either one of them,

02:38:32.000 --> 02:38:39.000
because there really are only a finite range of possibilities if you make the game end at a certain point,

02:38:39.000 --> 02:38:43.000
it's a combinatorial problem in the end.

02:38:43.000 --> 02:38:50.000
Now, obviously AlphaZero doesn't solve the problem in a combinatorial way.

02:38:50.000 --> 02:38:53.000
That would take too much energy.

02:38:53.000 --> 02:38:54.000
You couldn't do it.

02:38:54.000 --> 02:38:58.000
It sort of explodes the problem.

02:38:58.000 --> 02:39:03.000
So it does it in this other way that's interesting, this pattern recognition way, roughly.

02:39:03.000 --> 02:39:17.000
And in that context, it may well be that it can see, having had lots and lots of experience in the training stuff against itself or against another version of itself,

02:39:17.000 --> 02:39:22.000
it can see that the sacrifice here is going to pay dividends down the road.

02:39:22.000 --> 02:39:25.000
See, I put that in quotation marks.

02:39:25.000 --> 02:39:38.000
That's to say, it's got a high weight to this move here as a result of experience in the past where that move down the line led to this improvement.

02:39:38.000 --> 02:39:46.000
So in that finite context, I think the game-players can trust it, and they talk that way.

02:39:46.000 --> 02:39:49.000
It's got a kind of authority.

02:39:49.000 --> 02:39:58.000
They say, I've read some people who said about AlphaZero when it played Go, it's like it's playing from the future.

02:39:58.000 --> 02:40:08.000
It's making these moves that are just outlandish, and there's a kind of brilliance to them that we can't really understand.

02:40:08.000 --> 02:40:10.000
We'll be catching up to it forever.

02:40:10.000 --> 02:40:18.000
I think in that context, it's mapped the domain, and the domain is mappable because it's a combinatorial problem, roughly.

02:40:18.000 --> 02:40:41.000
But in something like music or art of a non-finite form, it feels to me like it's a little harder for me to understand what the analog of our trusting that Stravinsky has recognized something about us that demands that he write this way.

02:40:41.000 --> 02:40:45.000
That doesn't seem like a finite thing in quite the same way.

02:40:45.000 --> 02:40:49.000
Now, we could ask the system, why did you do it?

02:40:49.000 --> 02:40:52.000
We could ask Stravinsky, why did you do it?

02:40:52.000 --> 02:40:59.000
And maybe it will have answers, but then it's involved in a kind of communicative act.

02:40:59.000 --> 02:41:07.000
And I think lots of times, artists will often say, look, I can't communicate better than what I've done in the piece of work.

02:41:07.000 --> 02:41:09.000
That is the statement.

02:41:09.000 --> 02:41:10.000
Yeah, yeah.

02:41:10.000 --> 02:41:13.000
We humans aren't able to answer the why either.

02:41:13.000 --> 02:41:22.000
But I do think the question here is, well, first of all, language is finite, certainly when expressed through a tweet.

02:41:22.000 --> 02:41:25.000
So it is also a combinatorial problem.

02:41:25.000 --> 02:41:29.000
The question is how much more difficult it is than chess.

02:41:29.000 --> 02:41:46.000
And I think all the same ways that we see the solutions to chess is deeply surprising when it was first addressed with IBM Dblue and then with AlphaGo and AlphaGo Zero, AlphaZero.

02:41:46.000 --> 02:41:53.000
I think in that same way, language can be addressed and communication can be addressed.

02:41:53.000 --> 02:42:06.000
I don't see, having done this podcast, many reasons why everything I'm doing, especially as a digital being on the internet, can't be done by an AI system eventually.

02:42:06.000 --> 02:42:12.000
So I think we're being very human-centric and thinking we're special.

02:42:12.000 --> 02:42:29.000
I think one of the hardest things is the physical space, actually operating like touch and the magic of body language and the music of all of that because it's so deeply integrated through the long evolutionary process of what it's like to be on Earth.

02:42:29.000 --> 02:42:44.000
And what is fundamentally different and AI can catch up on is the way we apply our evolutionary history on the way we act on the internet and the way we act online.

02:42:44.000 --> 02:42:53.000
And as more and more of the world becomes digital, you're now operating in a space where AI is behind much less so.

02:42:53.000 --> 02:42:56.000
Like we're both starting at zero.

