I think that's super interesting. Do you know this author, Brian Christian? Is that someone you've ever heard of?

02:43:03.000 --> 02:43:04.000
Sounds familiar.

02:43:04.000 --> 02:43:09.000
He's a guy who competed in the, what is it called? The Lobner Competition.

02:43:09.000 --> 02:43:10.000
The Lobner Prize, yeah.

02:43:10.000 --> 02:43:12.000
Yeah, the Turing Test thing.

02:43:12.000 --> 02:43:21.000
So, and I'll just tell you the story, but I think it's directly related to the last thing you said about where we're starting in the same place.

02:43:21.000 --> 02:43:30.000
He competed in this competition, but not, he didn't enter a program that was supposed to try to pass the Turing Test.

02:43:30.000 --> 02:43:38.000
The Turing Test, you know, there's three people. There's the judge, there's the program, and then there's someone who's a human the way they do it.

02:43:38.000 --> 02:43:43.000
And the judge has got to figure out by asking questions, which is the computer and which is the human.

02:43:43.000 --> 02:43:47.000
So little known fact, there's two prizes in that competition.

02:43:47.000 --> 02:43:54.000
There's the most human computer prize. That's the computer that wins the most. And then there's the most human-human prize.

02:43:54.000 --> 02:44:00.000
And he competed for the most human-human prize. And he won it. He kept winning it.

02:44:00.000 --> 02:44:11.000
And so he tried to think about what it is that you have to be able to do in order to convince judges that you're human instead of a computer.

02:44:11.000 --> 02:44:14.000
And that's an interesting question, I think.

02:44:14.000 --> 02:44:29.000
And what he came to, my takeaway from his version of this story, is that it is true that computers are winning these contests more and more, you know, as technology progresses.

02:44:29.000 --> 02:44:36.000
But there's two possible explanations for that. One is that the computers are becoming more human.

02:44:36.000 --> 02:44:41.000
And the other is that the humans are becoming more like computers.

02:44:41.000 --> 02:45:01.000
And he says, actually, the more we live our lives in this world where, in this sort of technological world, where we have to moderate our behavior so that it's readable by something that's effectively, you know, a computer,

02:45:01.000 --> 02:45:09.000
the more we become like that. And he says, it happens even when you're not interacting with a computer.

02:45:09.000 --> 02:45:16.000
He says, have you ever been to the, you know, on the phone with a call, you know, center? And they're going through their script.

02:45:16.000 --> 02:45:21.000
And that's what they've got to do. They've got to go through their script, because that's how they keep their job.

02:45:21.000 --> 02:45:28.000
And they ask you this question, and you've got to answer it. And it's as if you're no longer interacting with a person, even though it's a person,

02:45:28.000 --> 02:45:38.000
because they've so given up everything that's involved normally with being able to make judgments and decisions and act in situations and take responsibility.

02:45:38.000 --> 02:45:52.000
And so I think that's the other side of it. It is true that technology is amazing and can solve huge ranges of problems and do fantastic things.

02:45:52.000 --> 02:46:08.000
It's also true that we're changing ourselves in response to it. And the one thing I'm worried about is that we're changing ourselves in such a way that the norms for what we're aiming at are being changed

02:46:08.000 --> 02:46:21.000
to move in the direction of this sort of efficiently in an optimized way, solving a problem and move away from this other kind of thing that we were calling aliveness or significance.

02:46:21.000 --> 02:46:25.000
And so that's the other side of the story.

02:46:25.000 --> 02:46:44.000
And that's the worry, but it's very possible that there is, for you and I, the ancient dinosaurs, we may not see the aliveness in TikTok, the aliveness in the digital space, that you see it as us being dragged into this over-optimized world.

02:46:44.000 --> 02:46:55.000
But that may be, this is, in fact, it is a world that opens up opportunities to truly experience life.

02:46:55.000 --> 02:47:05.000
And there's interesting to think about all the people growing up now, who their early experience of life is always mediated through a digital device,

02:47:05.000 --> 02:47:22.000
not always, but more and more often mediated through that device, and how we're both evolving, the technologies evolving and the humans are evolving, to then maybe open a door to a whole world where the humans and the technology or AI systems are interacting as equals.

02:47:22.000 --> 02:47:28.000
So now I'm going to agree with you. You might be surprised that I'm going to agree with you, but I think that's exactly right.

02:47:28.000 --> 02:47:37.000
